LOCATION

Hiyama [hi-ya-ma] [\u6A9C\u5C71] is a sub-prefecture (``shinkou-
kyoku'') in south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').  Hiyama is located in the 
west of the Oshima Peninsula.  It faces the Sea of Japan.  The area is 
divided into north and south.  #1
 	Climate in Hiyama is mild compared to other areas in Hokkaidou. 
The warm Tsushima Current in the Sea of Japan influences.  In winter, 
it is windy due to the monsoon that blows from the continent.
	According to Koeppen's climate classification, most of the 
areas in Hiyama are classified as Dfb (humid continental, cool summer). 
The coast of Esashi Town and the coast of Okushiri island are 
classified as Cfa (humid subtropical).  The other coasts are classified 
as Cfb (temperate oceanic).  The population is distributed along the 
coast.
	In the case of Esashi Town, the mean annual temperature is 10.1 
degrees Celsius (average from 1981 to 2010), the mean annual 
precipitation is 1,197 millimeters, and the mean snowfall is 330 
centimeters.  #2

NAME

The name ``Hiyama'' is Japanese. ``Hi-yama'' means ``cypress 
[sa'i-pruhs], mountain.''  The name was suggested by Takeshirou 
Matsuura in the beginning of the Meiji period.  Takeshirou Matsuura 
explored Ezo (now Hokkaidou) during the Edo era.  #3
	There used to be natural forests of Hiba trees in Hiyama. 
(Hiba is a kind of cypress.)  After the late 17th century, during the 
Edo era, the Matsumae Domain felled Hiba trees in the area what is now 
Hiyama sub-prefecture.  #4
	Japanese immigration has a long history.  In the mid 15th 
century, the Andou clan built 12 forts in what is now Hiayama and 
Oshima sub-prefectures.  In the Edo era, the south part of Hiyama was 
ruled by the Matsumae Domain.  (The area was also ruled by the Tokugawa 
Shogunate for a time.)  #5
	After the Meiji period, in 1869 (Meiji 2), the area was 
included in Oshima-no-kuni (Oshima country [\u6E21\u5CF6\u56FD]) and 
Shiribeshi-no-kuni (Shiribeshi country [\u5F8C\u5FD7\u56FD]).  In 1872 
(Meiji 5), Esashi branch of the Hokkaidou Development Commission was 
established.
	In 1897 (Meiji 30), Hiyama sub-prefecture (Hiyama-shichou 
[\u6A9C\u5C71 \u652F\u5E81] was established. In 2010, Hiyama Sub-
prefectural Bureau (Hiyama-shinkou-kyoku) was established.

MUNICIPALITY

These are municipalities in Hiyama; (1) Setana Town 9,590 (population 
in 2010), (2) Esashi Town 9,004, (3) Imakane Town 6,186, (4) Kaminokuni 
Town 5,428, (5) Assabu Town 4,409, (6) Otobe Town 4,408, and (7) 
Okushiri Town 3,033.  The sub-prefectural bureau is located in Esashi 
Town.
	The poplation of Hiyama is the smallest of all the sub-
prefectures.  All municipalities in Hiyama are designated as 
depopulated areas (``kaso-chiiki'').

NOTE
  
#1  Hiyama sub-prefecture is devided into two parts, the north and 
the south.  In the middle part, there was Kumaishi Town that was merged 
to Yakumo Town in Oshima sub-prefecture.  
	Oshima sub-prefecture is located on the Pacific Ocean side.  
Hiyama sub-prefecture is located on the Sea of Japal side.  There were 
many reasons for the merger across sub-prefectures.

#2  In the case of Tokyo (Chiyoda Ward; the representative data of 
Japan), the mean annual temperature is 15.4 degrees Celsius (average 
from 1981 to 2010) and the mean annual rainfall is 1,529 millimeters. 
The climate of Tokyo is classified as Cfa (humid subtropical) by 
Koeppen's climate classification.
	As for the coldest month, the mean temperature of Tokyo is 5.2 
degrees Celsius in January.  The mean temperature of Esashi is -0.8 
degrees Celsius in January.  As for the hottest month, the mean 
temperature of Tokyo is 26.4 degrees Celsius in August.  The mean 
temperature of Esashi is 22.6 degrees Celsius in August.
  
#3  Takeshirou Matsuura (1818-1888) was an explorer of Ezo (old 
Hokkaidou) in the Edo era.  He documented place names in Ezo island and 
published the book ``Ezochi-gunmei-no-gui-torishirabe-sho (Ezo region 
county name survey report) [\u8766\u5937\u5730\u90E1\u540D\u4E4B\u5100
\u53D6\u8ABF\u66F8].''
	The book was submitted to the Meiji government in 1869 (Meiji 
2).  The government decided place names in Ezo (now Hokkaidou). 
``Hiyama'' was the one of them.
	Before the Edo era, in the 15th century, the Andou clan 
migrated to Ezo and built 12 forts.  They returned to thier home land, 
which was located in what is now the Touhoku region.  In their home 
land, the Andou clan built Hiyama Castle, which was located in what is 
now Akita Prefecture.
	As for the name ``Hiyama,'' Takeshirou Matsuura may have 
adopted the name of the old castle that was built by the Andou clan in 
their home land.
	[See Kaminokuni Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for the former 12 
forts.]
 
#4  Regarding the name ``Hi-yama (cypress mountain),'' in Honshuu 
island, cypress trees usually means Hinoki trees.  In Hokkaidou and 
Aomori prefectures, cypress trees  means ``Hiba.''
	Houryuuji Temple is the oldest wooden building in the country. 
It was rebuilt in 670.  The temple is made of Hinoki trees. Temple 
carpenters (``miya-daiku'') consider Hinoki is the best wood for 
construction (Nihei lab 2024-2025a).
	[See Kaminokuni Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for the oldest 
building in Hokkaidou.]
	The another name of Hiba trees is Hinoki-asunaro.  It means 
``tomorrow, it will be Hinoki trees'' in Japanese.  This means that the 
wood of Hiba is inferior to Hinoki.  Actually, the wood of Hiba is also 
good.
	The leaves of Hiba are denser than Hinoki.  Hiba grows slower 
than trees of Hinoki, Sugui (ceder), and Todo-matsu (fir).  Hiba grows 
even on shady north slopes and moist soils along the coast.  It grows 
slowy and steadily.
	The wood of Hiba has a tight grain and is resistant to 
moisture.  The wood is less likely to warp and less likely to rot.  It 
was used for pillars, bathtubs, boats, bridges, and cutting boards.
	The natural forests of Hiba in Hiyama sub-prefecture were said 
``very good trees from the shoreline.''  The natural forests were 
disappeared for felling and fires during the Edo era.
	Today, two natural forests are preserved in remote mountains.  
They have been designated as National Natural Monuments.
	[See Assabu Town and Esashi Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for 
cypress felling.]
 
#5  Masao Kanamori, who is a high school teacher, says; ``Hiyama's 
culture is different from other parts of Hokkaidou.  You can see it 
when you visit festivals.''
