DATA

AREA 293 KM2 (2010), FOREST 256, CULTIVATED 4; COUNTY = MATSUMAE [\u677E
\u524D]; POP 8,748 (2010), 13,546 (1990); MEAN ANNUAL TEMP 10.3 C (AV 
1981-2010), PRECIPI 1,263 MM; COUNTRY SIGN = CASTLE.  
  
LOCATION

Matsumae [ma-tsu-ma-e] [\u677E\u524D] is a town in Oshima sub-
prefecture, south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').  The area is located in the 
southwest of the Oshima Peninsula.  This part of the Oshima Peninsula 
is called the Matsumae Peninsula.
	Matsumae is the southernmost municipality in Hokkaidou.  The 
area faces the Tsugaru Strait and the Sea of Japan.  It includes 
Ooshima island and Kojima island on the Sea of Japan.  #1  #2
 	The area is mountainous.  Forests occupy 87 percent. Rivers 
are short.  Mt. Dai-sen-guen (1,072 meters) stands to the north.  In 
the past, there was a gold mine in Mt. Dai-sen-guen.
	[See Fukushima Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for the gold 
miners in Mt. Dai-sen-guen.]
	The climate along the coast is humid subtropical.  It is 
classified as ``Cfa'' by Koeppen's climate classification. ``Cfa'' 
means ``humid subtropical.''  Almost all other parts of Hokkaidou are 
classified as ``Dfb,'' which means ``humid continental and cool 
summer.''
	Camellia trees and Mousou-dake bamboos grow under the warm 
climate of Matsumae Town.  Camellia is a forever-green broad-leaved 
tree.  It is a family of tea tree.  Mousou-dake is a large kind of 
bamboo.  In Hokkaidou, generally, the word ``bamboo'' signifies 
``bamboo grass (`sasa').''  

NAME

The name ``Matsumae'' comes from ``mat-oma-i'' in Ainu language.  It 
means ``woman, live, place.''  It signified the uniqueness of the place 
where Japanese women lived.  The etymology of the name is similar to 
Kuromatsunai Town in Shiribeshi sub-prefecture.
	In Ezo (old Hokkaidou), most Japanese people returned to their 
homelands in winter.  The name ``Matsumae'' signified that the place 
was the territory of Japanese people.  They could give birth 
(reproduce) in the place.

HISTORY

In 720, the name ``Watari-shima-tsugaru-tsu [\u6E21\u5CF6\u6D25\u8EFD
\u6D25]'' was recorded.  It meant a port (``tsu'') between Watari-shima 
(now Hokkaidou Prefecture) and Tsugaru (now Aomori Prefecture).  It 
signified what is now the Port of Matsumae.
	In the 14th century, the name ``Matouma-inu [\u4E07\u5802
\u5B87\u6E80\u4F0A\u72AC]'' was recorded.  From the 13th to 15th 
centuries, the Andou clan came from Tsugaru (now Aomori Prefecture).
They built 12 forts in what is now south Hokkaidou.  They traded with 
Ainu people.
	In 1457, Koshamain's War happened.  Koshamain was a chief of 
Ainu.  In the war, the Ainu forces destroyed 10 forts out of the 12 
forts, which the the Andou clan built.  #3
	[See Kaminokuni Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for the former 12 
forts and Koshamain's War.]
 	During the Edo era, Matsumae was the capital of the Matsumae 
Domain.  It was the northernmost castle town in Japan.  The Matsumae 
Domain managed major ports in Ezo (old Hokkaidou), namely, Matsumae, 
Esashi, and Hakodate.  Those ports were gateways to Ezo.  ``Matsmai'' 
in Moby Dick (a novel) means Hokkaidou.
 	In the end of the Edo era, in 1868, the Matsumae Domain seceded 
from the Tokugawa Shogunate.  They supported the new Meiji government.  
In the beginning of the Meiji period, the Boshin War happened.  The 
former Tokugawa Shogunate forces landed Ezo and captured Fukuyama 
Castle and the capital of the Matsumae Domain. (Another name of 
Fukuyama Castle is Matsumae Castle.)
	In 1869 (Meiji 2), the Meiji government forces recaptured 
Fukuyama Castle.  They advanced to Hakodate, defeated the former 
Tokugawa Shogunate, and ended the Boshin War.  After the war, the 
Matsumae Domain was renamed the Tate Domain.  It was named after Tate 
Castle in what is now Assabu Town.
	[See Hakodate City in Oshima sub-prefecture for the Boshin War. 
See Assabu Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for Tate Castle.]
 	In 1871 (Meiji 4), the Tate Domain was abolished and Aomori 
Prefecture governed the southern part of Hokkaidou.  In 1872 (Meiji 5), 
Matsumae branch of the Hokkaidou Development Commission (Kaitaku-shi) 
was established.
	In 1881 (Meiji 14), the administrative office of Matsumae 
county (Matsumae-gun-yakusho) was established.  Matsumae branch of the 
Hokkaidou Development Commission was abolished.  In 1897 (Meiji 30), 
Matsumae sub-prefecture was established.  The administrative office of 
Matsumae county was abolished.
	In 1900 (Meiji 33), Fukuyama [\u798F\u5C71] Town (1st-class 
municipality) was established.  At the time, 34 towns in the built-up 
area of Matsumae were merged. (The area of the towns in a built-up area 
are small.  They were established in the Edo era.)  #4
	In 1903 (Meiji 36), Hakodate sub-prefecture merged Matsumae 
sub-prefecture.  In 1915 (Taishou 4), Ooshima [\u5927\u5CF6] Village 
(2nd-class municipality) was established by the merger of three 
villages; Eramachi [\u6C5F\u826F\u753A], Haraguchi [\u539F\u53E3], and 
Kiyobe [\u6E05\u90E8].  (Ooshima village was not Ooshima island.)
	In 1923 (Taishou 12), Kojima [\u5C0F\u5CF6] Village (2nd-class 
municipality) was established by the merger of five villages; Nebuta 
[\u6839\u90E8\u7530], Akagami [\u8D64\u795E], Satsumae [\u672D\u524D], 
Mogusa [\u8302\u8349], and Utari [\u96E8\u5782].  (Kojima village was 
not in Kojima island.)
	In the same year, Oosawa [\u5927\u6CA2] Village (2nd-class 
municipality) was established by the merger of four villages; Oosawa, 
Araya [\u8352\u8C37], Sumiyaki-zawa [\u70AD\u713C\u6CA2], and Kami-
oyobe [\u4E0A\u53CA\u90E8].  #5
	In 1940 (Shouwa 15), Fukuyama Town was renamed Matsumae Town. 
In 1954 (Shouwa 29), Matsumae Town merged the villages of Ooshima, 
Kojima, and Oosawa.

TOWN HALL, TRAFFIC

The town hall of Matsumae and Matsumae Castle (Fukuyama Castle) are 
located near the mouth of the Oomatsumae River.  National Route 228 
(Fukuyama-kaidou or Matsumae-kokudou) passes there.  ``Fukuyama-
kaidou'' was an old trail that connected Matsumae and Hakodate in the 
Edo era.  #6
	[See Fukushima Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for Fukuyama-
kaidou.]
 	In the past, the Matsumae Line run.  The railroad connected 
Kikonai Town and Matsumae Town.  The terminal was Matsumae Station.  
The population of Matsumae peaked at 20,072 in 1955.  #7

INDUSTRY, CULTURE

Distinctive industries in Matsumae are fishery, food processing (mainly 
Surume and Matsumae-zuke), and sightseeing.  STATISTICS OF AGRICULTURE 
= fodder 192 hectares in 2015, pasture 154, and paddy rice X 
(concealed); dairy cows - (zero) in 2015.  STATISTICS OF FISHERIES = 
squid (flying squid 540 tons in 2017, other squid 154), snow crabs 442, 
	(continued) --> atka mackerel 334, sea urchins 126, tuna 92, 
Pacific cod 61, Konbu kelp (cultured) 57, octopus 49, sharks 47, olive 
flounder 6, shrimp/prawns 5, walleye pollock 4, abalone (cultured) 2, 
yellowtail 1, herring -, other fish 29+X, and other marine animals 11.
#8
	As for sightseeing, Matsumae Castle is famous for cherry 
blossoms.  In the castle, there is a botanical garden with 10,000 
cherry trees of 250 varieties.  #9
	There are many temples in Matsumae, as it was a castle town.  
In the past, monks were like civil servants.  They could read and 
write.  Today, Tourists observe buildings and gardens in temples. 
 
NOTE
 
#1  The southernmost of Hokkaidou island is Cape Shirakami.  It is 
located along National Route 228 in Matsumae Town.  The latitude is 41 
degrees 23.87 minutes north.  The longitude is 140 degrees 11.86 
minutes east.
 	If small islands are counted, the southernmost of Hokkaidou 
Prefecture is Kojima island.  Kojima island is also called Matsumae-
kojima or Oshima-kojima.  It is an uninhabited island.
	Ooshima island is the largest uninhabited island in the 
country.  The area is 9.7 square kilometers. Ooshima island is also 
called Matsumae-ooshima or Oshima-ooshima.
