and Tsugaru Peninsula.  The water is shallower, although the distance 
is longer.
	[See Hakaodate City in Oshima sub-prefecture for the Tsugaru 
Strait.]
 
#3  In 1457, the warlord Nobuhiro Takeda ended the Koshamain's War. 
Nobuhiro Takeda was a vassal of the Andou clan.  Around 1549, his 
great-grandson, Suehiro Kakizaki, made peace with Ainu chiefs.
	[See Kaminokuni Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for Nobuhiro 
Takeda.] 
	In 1593, Yoshihiro Kakizaki, who was the son of Suehiro 
Kakizaki, became independent from the Andou clan.  He was able to ask 
Hideyoshi Toyotomi for the land of Ezo (now Hokkaidou).  (Hideyoshi 
Toyotomi was the ruler during the Warring State era.)
	The meeting between Hideyoshi Toyotomi and Yoshihiro Kakizaki 
was arranged by the Maeda clan. The Maeda clan was the ruler of the 
Kaga Domain (now Ishikawa Prefecture).
	In 1598, Hideyoshi Toyotomi died. In 1599, Yoshihiro Kakizaki 
gave Ezo maps to Ieyasu Tokugawa, who founded the Tokugawa Shogunate. 
Maps were important for governing lands during the Warring States era. 
Giving maps meant obedience.
	In 1604, in the Edo era, the Tokugawa Shogunate appointed 
Yoshihiro Kakizaki as the lord of the Matsumae Domain. Yoshihiro 
Kakizaki changed his family name from Kakizaki to Matsumae.
	There is a rummer that the name ``Matsu-mae'' comes from 
Matsudaira (Ieyasu Tokugawa's old family name) and the Maeda clan.
	(The Tokugawa Shogunate continued from 1903 to 1867. The 
founder Ieyasu Tokugawa moved the capital from Kyouto to Edo [now 
Tokyo].)
 
#4  In Hokkaidou, 1st-class (``ikkyuu'') municipalities and 2nd-class 
(``nikyuu'') municipalities were designated from 1899 to 1943.  The 
Hokkaidou government subsidized 2nd-class municipalities.  It was a 
pioneering period.
 
#5   As for the former Sumiyaki-zawa village, the name ``Sumi-yaki-
zawa'' means ``charcoal, burn, stream'' in Japanese.
	Sei Itou was a novelist who was born in Sumiyaki-zawa village.  
He was influenced by James Joyce, an Irish novelist.  He was one of the 
translators of Ulysses.  The Japanese translation of Ulysses was 
published from 1931 to 1933.)
	[See Otaru City in Shiribeshi sub-prefecture for Sei Itou.]
	James Joyce published his novels in English.  He did not use 
his native language Celtic in his work.  He died in Zurich.  Not only 
James Joyce but also Jonathan Swift, William Butler Yeats, and Oscar 
Wild were from Ireland and published their work in English.  They had 
the guts.

#6  Fukuyama Castle is the former name of Matsumae Castle.  The castle 
was designated as a national treasure of Japan.  The castle burned down 
in 1949.
	Currently, the only national treasure in Hokkaidou is a clay 
figurine.  It was dug out from a potato field.
	[See Hakodate City in Oshima sub-prefecture for the national 
treasure.]

#7  Matsumae Town is a sister city with Oumi-hachiman City in Shiga 
Prefecture and Yanagawa Town (now Date City) in Fukushima Prefecture. 
The reasons date back to the Edo era;
	Merchants from Oumi-hachiman were called Hachiman-shounin. 
They traded in Ezo using Kitamae-bune (North-bound ship).  They 
based in the castle town of Matsumae.  They developed herring fishing 
grounds.  (Hachiman-shounin was included in Oumi-shounin [Oumi 
merchants].)
	Regarding Yanagawa, in 1807, the Tokugawa Shogunate directly 
ruled Ezo to prevent Russian southward movement.  The Mastumae Domain's 
attitude towards the Russians was judged to be bad.  The vassals of 
Matsumae Domain were forced to moved to Yanagawa. 
	Half of the vassals became ``rounin'' (jobless samurai).  They 
lived in hardship for 14 years until the Matsumae Domain was returned 
to Ezo in 1821.

#8  Dried flying squid is called ``surume.''  Matsumae Town and 
neighboring Fukushima Town are the largest producers of dried flying 
squid in the country.
	 The tonnages of dried flying squid from those towns account 
for 80 percent of the national share.  In the late Meiji period (about 
100 years ago), herring fishing decreased and flying squid fishing 
prospered.
	In the past, fishers processed flying squid into ``surume'' 
(dried flying squid).  As catches increased, after the 1970s, local 
companies started processing flying squid.  ]By Matsumae Town's website 
``History of Matsumae Surume,'' last accessed May 2019.]
	Matsumae-zuke is pickles made with Konbu kelp, dried flying 
squid, and herring roe.  A variety of Matsumae-zuke are sold at 
``Dosanko Plaza,'' a souvenir shop in Sapporo Station.
	In the past, when herring catches were poor, Matsumae-zuke 
without herring roe was sold.

#9  These are famous cherry blossom sites in Hokkaidou; (1) Matsumae 
Castle (in Matsumae Town, Oshima sub-prefecture), (2) Go-ryou-kaku 
Castle (in Hakodate City, Oshima sub-prefecture), (3) Rows of cherry 
trees that lead to Noboribetsu Hot Spring (in Noboribetsu City, Iburi 
sub-prefecture), 
	(continued) --> (4) Nijikken Road in Shizunai (in what is now 
Shin-hidaka Town, Hidaka sub-prefecture), and (5) Shiokari Pass (in 
Wassamu Town in Kamikawa sub-prefecture).
	These are cherry varieties and cherry blossom sites; (1) 
Yaezakura (double-flowered cherry) and many other varieties including 
Somei-yoshino in Matsumae Castle, (2) Somei-yoshino in Go-ryou-kaku 
Castle, (3) and Ezo-yamazakura (Hokkaidou mountain cherry) in Shizunai.
	The best time to see cherry blossoms varies year by year. 
Generally, it is from late April to mid May in Matsumae Town and from 
early to mid May in Shizunai.
	One of the oldest Somei-yoshino trees in the country exists at 
Matsumae Castle.  It was planted in 1882 (Meiji 15).
	Somei-yoshino is a famous cherry variety in the country.  It 
was bred in Somei village near Edo (now the center of Tokyo) in the end 
of the Edo era.  Somei village was located near present-day Ikebukuro.
	Somei-yoshino was named after Mt. Yoshino, a famous cherry 
blossom site in Nara Prefecture.  The cherries in Mt. Yoshino are 
mountain cherries.
	Somei-yoshino trees are clones. If the soil and climate are the 
same, they grow in the same way.  The height, trunk diameter, twisted 
trunk, and blooming period are similar.  Somei-yoshino trees are used 
as an indicator for the season of cherry blossom. 
	Making plant clones are easier than animal clones.  Clones are 
more alike than siblings.  Plant clones are the predecessors of today's 
digital society (Nihei lab 2023-2025b).
