LOCATION

Fukushima [fu-ku-shi-ma] [\u798F\u5CF6] is a town in Oshima sub-
prefecture, south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').  The area faces the Tsugaru 
Strait to the south.  The Fukushima River and the Shiriuchi River flow.
	Forests cover 93 percent of the area.  Mt. Dai-sen-guen (1,072 
meters) rises to the north.  Matsumae county consists of Matsumae Town 
and Fukushima Town and is located at the southern end of Hokkaidou.

NAME

The name ``Fukushima'' is Japanese.  ``Fuku-shima'' means 
``lucky, island.''  It is a good-luck name that was given by an oracle 
from Tsukizaki Shrine in 1624.  #1  #2

HISTORY

The first Japanese immigrants to Ezo (now Hokkaidou) came from Ooshuu 
(now Touhoku region) in 1189.  They were vassals of the Fujiwara clan 
that were defeated by Yoritomo Minamoto.  They lived in what is now 
Yoshioka district, Fukushima Town.  (Yoritomo Minamoto established the 
Kamakura Shogunate after he conquered Ooshuu.)  
	In the mid 15th century, there was a fort called Onnai-date in 
Yoshioka district.  The fort was destroyed by the Ainu forces during 
Koshamain's War.
	[See Kaminokuni Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for Koshamain's 
war.]
	In the Edo era, this area was ruled by the Matsumae Domain. 
Around 1617, a gold mine opened in Mt. Dai-sen-guen.  The gold miners 
were Catholic.  #3
 	In the beginning of the Meiji period, this area belonged to the 
Tate Domain.  (The Matsumae domain was renamed the Tate Domain.)
	[See Matsumae Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for the Tate 
Domain.]
	In 1879 (Meiji 12), two administrative offices (``kochou-
yakuba'') were established; one was for Fukushima village and Shirafu 
[\u767D\u7B26] village; one was for Yoshioka [\u5409\u5CA1] village, 
Reihige [\u793C\u9AED] village, and Miyanouta [\u5BAE\u6B4C] village.
 	In 1900 (Meiji 33), Fukushima Village (1st-class municipality) 
was established by the merger of Fukushima village and Shirafu village. 
	[See the note of Matsumae Town for 1st-class and 2nd-class 
municipalities.]
	In 1902 (Meiji 35), Yoshioka Village (2nd-class municipality) 
was established by the merger of Yoshioka, Reihige, and Miyanouta 
villages.  In 1944 (Shouwa 19), Fukushima Town was established.  In 
1955 (Shouwa 30), Fukushima Town and Yoshioka Village were merged.
 	
TOWN HALL, TRAFFIC

The town hall of Fukushima is located near the mouth of the Fukushima 
River.  National Route 228 (Fukuyama-kaidou) runs.  #4
 	In the past, the Matsumae Line ran.  It connected Matsumae 
Station in Matsumae Town and Kikonai Station in Kikonai Town.  There 
was Yoshioka-kaitei Station on the Kaikyou Line.  It was an undersea 
station in the undersea Seikan Tunnel.  #5

INDUSTRY

Distinctive industries in Fukushima are fishery and forestry. 
STATISTICS OF AGRICULTIRE = paddy rice X (concealed) in 2015; dairy 
cows - (zero) in 2015.  STATISTICS OF FISHERIES = squid (flying squid 
895 tons in 2017, other squid 26), sea urchins 85, tuna 66, octopus 48, 
	(continud) --> seaweed (Konbu kelp 24, other seaweed 10), olive 
flounder 6, sea trout 6, atka mackerel 6, right-eye flounder 1, abalone 
1, herring 0, other fish 10, and other marine animals 3. 
	Fishing ports are located in Fukushima, Yoshioka, Shirafu, and 
Urawa.  The catch of squid accounts for about 80 percent of the 
fishery.  Fukushima and neighboring Matsumae are the leading producers 
of ``surume'' (dried flying squid) in the country.
	[See Matsumae Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for ``surume.'']
	As for forestry, the main trees are cedar [si'-dar], fir (Todo-
matsu), and spruce (Ezo-matsu).  The ceder is sold under the trade-name 
Dou-nan-sugui (South Hokkaidou Cedar).  #6
	Sightseeing destinations include Seikan Tunnel Memorial Hall, 
Tadataka Inou Hokkaidou Survey Memorial Park, and Yokozuna Chiyo-no-
Yama and Chiyo-no-Fuji Memorial Hall.  ``Yokozuna'' means the champions 
of Sumou wrestling.
	[See Kaminokuni Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for Tadataka 
Inou.]
	The country sign (gateway sign) of Fukushima Town features a 
squid Sumou wrestler.  The name of the roadside station is Yokozuna-no-
sato, which means the hometown of Sumou champions.
 
NOTE

#1  According to ``Fukushima Town History (Fukushima-chou-shi) Volume 
2'' published in 1995, ``Once upon a time, Orikanai village was on the 
verge of being abandoned, for a large fire and poor fishing.  At the 
time, there was an oracle from Tsukisaki Shrine.  It said, `The name 
Orikanai must be changed to Fukushima.'
	The name ``Fuku-shima'' may have referred to Fuku-yama, which 
was a neighboring castle town.  ``Fuku-shima'' means ``lucky, island'' 
and ``Fuku-yama'' means ``lucky, mountain.''  Fukuyama was the former 
name of Matsumae Town.
	As for the original place name ``Orikanai,'' it comes from 
``horka-nay'' in Ainu language.  It means ``reverse, river.''  It 
signified the Fukushima River.  Seawater entered the estuary at high 
tide.  The etymology is the same as Horokanai Town in Kamikawa sub-
prefecture.

#2  These are old shrines in Fukushima Town; (1) Tsukisaki Shrine, 
reconstructed in 1492, (2) Fukushima Daijinguu Shrine, reconstructed in 
1573, (3) Shirafu Daijinguu Shrine, established in 1655 by the Matsumae 
Domain, and (4) Kamaya Shrine, established in 1772.
	Shirafu Daijinguu Shirine preserves the traditional dance 
``Shirafu-arauma-odori (Shirafu, wild horse, dance).''  The dance 
represented the power of the Matsumae Domain.  It has been designated 
as an Intangible Cultural Property (Mukei-bunka-zai).
	Kamaya Shrine is located in Shiogama district.  ``Shio-gama'' 
is Japanese, which means ``salt, pot.''  The name was derived from 
the production of salt for sardine fishing.

#3  The mountain's name ``Dai-sen-guen'' is Japanese.  It means 
``large, thousand, houses.''  It signified that there were 1,000 houses 
of gold miners.  During the Edo era, the Tokugawa Shogunate banned 
Christianity, however, the regulation was loose in Ezo island, because 
the island was considered as an outer land (``gaichi''). 
	In 1637, Christians revolted in Kyuushuu island.  In 1939, 
Christians in Ezo island were executed.  At the site of the gold mine 
in Mt. Dai-sen-guen, there is an inscription that reads ``Christian 
martyrdom [ma'r-tar-dam].''
 
#4  As for Fukuyama-kaidou (Fukuyama trail), the name ``Fukuyama'' 
means the former castle town of the Matsumae Domain.  The Fukuyama-
kaidou connected Fukuyama Castle (Matsume Castle) and the Port of 
Hakodate.  It was an old trail traveled by Matsumae Domain's samurai.  
The distance was 100 kilometers.
	Fukuyama-kaidou was located in Ezo (now Hokkaidou Prefecture). 
Matsumae-kaidou was located in Tsugaru (now Aomori Prefecture).
	[See Hokuto City in Oshima sub-prefecture for Matsumae-kaidou.]

#5  The Seikan Tunnel is an undersea railway tunnel.  The length is 54 
kilometers.  (Channel Tunnel [Le tunnel sous la Mance] between England 
and France is 50 kilometers.  Gotthard Base Tunnel in Switzerland is 
57 kilometers.)  Cf. The total length of tunnels in a coal mine 
reached 200 kilometers.
	[See Akabira City in Sorachi sub-prefecture for the coal 
mining.]
	Yoshioka-kaitei Station in Fukushima Town was built at 150 
meters below sea level.  The station was used for sightseeing and the 
maintenance of the undersea tunnel.  The station was closed in 2006 and 
demolished in 2014. 
 	Yoshioka district was the base for the construction of the 
undersea Seikan Tunnel.  It was constructed between 1961 and 1988. 
Yoshioka district flourished during the construction of the tunnel.  
	[See Kikonai Town and Hakodate City in Oshima sub-prefecture 
for the undersea tunnel.]

#6  Cedar trees are not common in Hokkaidou.  Cedar pollen fever is 
rare in the island.  However, white birch (``Shira-kanba'') and alder 
(``Han-no-ki'') cause pollen fever in Hokkaidou.  I did not hear about 
pollen fever when I was a child during the 1970s.  Cedar trees were 
young at the time. 
	Cedar trees grow on wet land.  Farmers in Honshuu island 
planted cedar trees on abandoned rice paddies near valley heads.  
During the high economic growth period, between the late 1960s and the 
early 1970s, farm successors left the countryside.  Land use was 
changed from agricultural to forest.  Taxes were reduced.
