LOCATION

Shiriuchi [shi-ri-u-chi] [\u77E5\u5185] is a town in Oshima sub-
prefecture, south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').  Shiriuchi is located in the 
southwest of the Oshima Peninsula.  This part of the Oshima Peninsula 
is called the Matsumae Peninsula.  The area of Shiriuchi faces the 
Tsugaru Strait to the east.  Forests cover 87 percent of the area.

NAME

The name ``Shiriuchi`` comes from ``cir-ot-i'' in Ainu language.  It 
means ``bird, exist, place.''  It signified the Shiriuchi River.  In 
the Edo era, Shiriuchi was a hunting ground for hawks and falcons.  
Young hawks and falcons were caught and shipped to Edo (now Tokyo) for 
falconry.  #1

HISTORY

In 1205, the feudal lord of Kai Province (now Yamanashi Prefecture) 
started gold dust gathering along the Shiriuchi River.  It was an order 
from the Kamakura Shogunate.
	In the 15th century, there was a fort called Wakimoto-date [da-
te].  It was one of the 12 forts built by the Andou clan.  The Andou 
clan came from Tsugaru (now Aomori Prefecture).  During the Edo era, 
the area what is now Shiriuchi was ruled by the Matsumae Domain.  #2
	After the Meiji period, in 1871 (Meiji 4), the administrative 
office (``kochou-yakuba'') of Shiriuchi village was established.  It 
was a continuation of village chief system from the Edo era.
	In 1881 (Meiji 14), the administrative office (``kochou-
yakuba'') of Shiriuchi village was re-established.  It covered 
Kotaniishi [\u5C0F\u8C37\u77F3] village.  [by ``Shin-Shiriuchi-choushi 
[new Shiriuchi Town history]'' published in 2015.]
	In 1906 (Meiji 39), Shiriuchi Village (2nd-class municipality) 
was established by the merger of Shiriuchi village and Kotaniishi 
village.  In 1967 (Shouwa 42), Shiriuchi Town was established.
	[See the note of Matsumae Town for 2nd-class municipality.] 

TOWN HALL, TRAFFIC

 	The town hall of Shiriuchi is located near the mouth of the 
Shiriuchi River.  National Route 228 (Fukuyama-kaidou) runs.  The name 
``Fukuyama'' means the castle town of the Matsumae Domain.
 	The national route runs along the coast, goes inland near the 
town hall, and leads to Fukushima Town.  Previously, there was 
Oshima-shiriuchi Station on the Matsumae Line.
	(The Matsumae Line was operated by Japanese National Railways 
[``Kokutetsu''[ until 1987.  The rialroad was abolished in 1988 after 
the management was transferred to JR Hokkaidou.)
	There was Shiriuchi Station on the Kaikyou Line. It became a 
roadside station (Michi-no-eki).  Visitors can watch the Shinkansen 
coming out of the undersea tunnel.  #3

INDUSTRY

Distinctive industries in Shiriuchi are agriculture, fishery, forestry, 
and power generation.  STATISTICS OF AGRICULTURE = paddy rice 422 
hectares in 2015, soybeans 124, buckwheat 85, pasture 54, fodder 18, 
	(continued) --> spinach 14, wheat 3, potatoes 2, orchards 1, 
flowers 1, and other vegetables 95+X (including Nira [Chinese chive or 
gynmigit]); dairy cows 112 head in 2015.  STATISTICS OF FISHERIES = s
quid (flying squid 296 tons in 2017, other squid 20), salmon 66, 
	(continued) --> sea urchins 30, seaweed 13 (Konbu kelp), 
shellfish 11 (oysters), olive flounder 10, right-eye flounder 6 
(marbled flounder), octopus 5, anchovy 4, yellowtail 4, sharks 1, 
mackerel 1, herring 0, other fish 20, and other marine animals 3.
 	According to a study on agricultural regionalization, the town 
was classified as a ``small-scale, single-crop, paddy rice'' area.  Due 
to the decrease in rice consumption, paddy rice decreased and Nira 
(Chinese chive) increased.
	Today, Shiriuchi is the largest producer of Nira in Hokkaidou. 
Nira is cultivated in greenhouses and harvested from January to 
October.  Nira is the vegetable included in Gyouza dumplings.  #4  #5 
 
NOTE
 
#1  In the Edo era, the Matsumae Domain traded hawks and falcons.  (In 
Japanese language, hawk is ``taka'' and falcon is ``hayabusa.'')  There 
were many bird-catching places in Ezo (now Hokkaidou).  Shiriuchi was 
one of the best places.
	Hawk catchers (``taka-machi'') searched for hawk (and falcon) 
nests in summer.  They wintered in Ezo, caught hawk chicks in spring, 
and gave them to the Matsumae Domain.  The birds were shipped to Edo 
(now Tokyo).  The Tokugawa Shogunate trained them for falcony.  
Feathers of hawks were also traded for making arrow fletchings.
	Ainu people also caught hawks (and falcons).  They sold hawks 
to Japanese people.  Ainu hunters hid in huts nearby streams, using 
salmon as lure.  When hawks appeared, Ainu hunters caught them by 
hooking their legs.
	Ainu people also kept hawks to take feathers.  They also kept 
young bears.  To them, bears were gods.
	[See Noboribetsu City in Iburi sub-prefecture for bear ranch.]

#2  Shiriuchi Town has a long history of Japanese immigration.  
Wakimoto Shrine in Kitsune-goshi district was established in 1239.  
Raikou Shrine in the center of the town was established in 1244. 
Shiriuchi Hot Spring was discovered by gold miners in 1247.  These are 
very old shrines and a hot spring in Hokkaidou. 
	Shrines in the Tama Hills of Tokyo, where I live now, are 
much newer than those in Shiriuchi Town.  In the past, priests at 
shrines were like village chiefs, because they could write documents.
	Fort Wakimoto-date was located in Wakimoto district in 
Shiriuchi Town.  It was located near Cape Kitsune-goshi.  The fort was 
destroyed by the Ainu forces during Koshamain's War.
	[See Kaminokuni Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for Koshamain's 
War.] 
	* * * 
	Cape Kitsune-goshi is located to the south of Wakimoto 
district.  Wakimoto is one of the oldest villages in Hokkaidou.  The 
name ``Kitsune-goshi'' is Japanese, which means ``fox, pass.''
	To the west of Cape Kitsune-goshi is Kotaniishi district.  To 
the west of Kotaniishi district is Cape Yagoshi.  The name ``Ya-goshi'' 
is Japanese, which means ``arrow, pass.''
	 Cape Yagoshi is a sea cliff whose altitude is 121 meters.  The 
road along the sea is a dead end.  

#3  At the observatory of Shiriuchi Roadside Station, there is a time 
table for the Shinkansen trains (bullet trains) entering and leaving 
the undersea Seikan Tunnel.
	Part of the former Shiriuchi Station on the Kaikyou Line became 
Yu-no-sato Signal Station.  Yu-no-sato Signal Station is the end of the 
undersea tunnel.  There was another Yu-no-sato Station on the former 
Matsumae Line.
	The name ``Yu-no-sato'' is Japanese, which means ``village of 
hot spring.'' Yu-no-sato is a district along the Shiriuchi River.  
There is Shiriuchi Hot Spring.
	[See Kikonai Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for the Kaikyou 
Line.]
 
#4  Oysters are cultivated in the open sea in Shiriuchi.  It is a 
unique method.  Generally, oysters are cultivated along the coast. 
Shiriuch Oysters are advertised at tasting events in Susukino.  
(Susukino is the largest entertainment district in Hokkaidou.  It is 
located in Chuuou Ward, Sapporo City.)
	As for power generation, Shiriuchi Power Plant is located in 
Motomachi district.  Hokkaidou Electric Power Company runs it. The 
power station uses heavy oil and Orimulsion. Orimulsion is a new fossil 
fuel.
	In summer, the power plant sells electricity to Tokyo Electric 
Power Company.  Tokyo metropolitan areas consume a huge amount of 
electricity in summer.  The climate is hot and humid.
	The electricity is transmitted through the undersea Seikan 
Tunnel.  The power cables are direct current (``choku-ryuu'').  Direct 
current is suitable for high voltage and long-distance transmission. 
Generally, electricity is transmitted as alternating current 
(``kouku-ryuu'').
 
#5  As for sightseeing, Shiriuchi is the hometown of Saburou Kitajima, 
a famous Enka singer.  Enka is a traditional style Japanese music. 
There is Saburou Kitajima Memorial Museum in Hakodate City.
	When I guided an excursion in Tokyo, we happened to pass by the 
Enka singer's residence.  It was near the former site of another Enka 
singer's residence.  Students did not know them.  Time has passed.
 	This is one of Kitajima's famous songs;
``Yosaku-wa-ki-wo-kiru, hey hey hoo
  (Yosaku cuts trees, hey hey hoo).''
	When I hear this song, I imagine a forestry office (``eirin-
sho'') in Hokkaidou.  Forests are vast in the north island.
