LOCATION

Kikonai [ki-ko-na-i] [\u6728\u53E4\u5185] is a town in Oshima sub-
prefecture, south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').  Kikonai is located in the 
southwest of the Oshima Peninsula.  This part of the Oshima peninsula 
is called the Matsumae Peninsula.  The area of Kikonai faces the 
Tsugaru Strait.  Forests cover 88 percent of the area.

NAME

The name ``Kikonai'' is derived from ``rir-o-nay'' in Ainu language.  
It means ``tide, enter, stream.''  It signified the Kikonai River.  
Saltwater entered the estuary at high tide.

HISTORY

In the 15th century, Nakano-date (Fort Nakano) existed.  That was one 
of 12 forts in Ezo (old Hokkaidou).
	[See Kaminokuni Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for the former 
12 forts.]
	In the Edo era, the Matsumae Domain ruled this area.  The name 
``Kikonai'' appears on the map of Ezo, which was drawn by the Matsumae 
Domain in 1624.
	After the Meiji period, in 1879 (Meiji 12), the administrative 
office (``kochou-yakuba'') of Kikonai village was established.  In 1902 
(Meiji 35), Kikonai Village (2nd-class municipality) was established by 
the merger of four villages; Kikonai, Kamatani [\u91DC\u8C37], 
Izumisawa [\u6CC9\u6CA2], and Sakkari [\u672D\u82C5].
	In 1919 (Taishou 8), Kikonai Village (1st-class municipality) 
was established.  In 1942 (Shouwa 17), Kikonai Town was established.  
#1  #2
	[See the note of Matsumae Town for 1st-class and 2nd-class 
municipalities.]

TOWN HALL, TRAFFIC

The town hall of Kikonai is located near the mouth of the Kikonai 
River.  National Route 228 (Fukuyama-kaidou) runs.  Kikonai is a 
station on the Hokkaidou Shinkansen.  Kikonai is also the terminal of 
the Dou-nan Isaribi Railway.  #3
	The name ``Isaribi'' is Japanese.  It means ``fishing lamp.''
Lamps for squid fishing float on the sea.  The fishing season for squid 
is from June to December.
	[See Hakodate City and Matsumae Town in Oshima sub-prefecture 
for squid fishing.]
 	In the past, the Esashi Line and the Matsumae Line ran.  
Kikonai was a transportation hub in the Matsumae Peninsula.  
Governmental offices were located in the center of the town such as a 
summary court, a forestry office (``eirin-sho''), and a railway yard by 
Japanese National Railways (``Koku-tetsu'').  #4

INDUSTRY, CULTURE

Distinctive industries in Kikonai are fishery, agriculture, animal 
husbandry (including Hakodate Wagyuu Beef), and forestry (including 
Dou-nan Ceder).  STATISTICS OF AGRICULTURE = paddy rice 291 hectares in 
2015, pasture 188, fodder 26, orchards 5, potatoes 4, spinach 2, 
	(continued) --> soybeans 1, radishes 1, and yams 1; dairy cows 
291 head in 2015, and beef cattle X (concealed).  STATISTICS OF 
FISHERIERS = salmon 65 tons in 2017 (autumn salmon), sea urchins 22, 
seaweed 18 (Konbu, Wakame, and Iwa-nori kelps), 
	(continued) --> shellfish (abalone 1, other shellfish 15), 
olive flounder 14, right-eye flounder 9 (marbled flounder), octopus 8, 
mackerel 5, sharks 4, yellowtail 1, Pacific cod 1, herring 0, other 
fish 7, and other marine animals 6.  #5
	The country sign (gateway sign) of Kikonai signifies Kanchuu-
misogui festival.  The name ``Kanchuu-misogui'' means ``winter, 
purification'' in Japanese.  The festival has been held since 1831.  
	During the festival, practitioners enter the sea in January.  
The temperature of the sea in winter is warmer than lakes and rivers, 
however, the location is Hokkaidou island.
 
NOTE
 
#1  During the Boshin War, the battle of Kikonai happened in 1869 
(Meiji 2).  The Meiji government forces advanced from Esashi to 
Hakodate.  The former Tokugawa Shogunate forces counter-attacked. 
	One of the routes taken by the Meiji government forces was the 
Kikonai mountain trail (Kikonai-sandou).  The commander of the former 
Tokugawa Shogunate was Keisuke Ootori.
	After being defeated in the Boshin War, Keisuke Ootori was 
imprisoned.  He was released and served for the Meiji government.  He 
became Japan's ambassador to Korea.
	During the Edo era, Keisuke Ootori studied Western medicine, 
learned English from John Manjirou, imported Western-style military 
tactics.  (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C5%8Ctori_Keisuke)
	[See Hakodate City in Oshima sub-prefecture for the Boshin 
War.]

#2  In 1871 (Meiji 4), Kanrin-maru (a ship) sank at Cape Saraki in 
Kikonai.  The anchor of the ship is displayed in Kikonai Town's museum. 
Along National Route 228, there is a monument to the ship that reads 
``End-of-Kanrin-mauru.''
	Kanrin-maru was a battleship that the Tokugawa Shogunate 
purchased from the Netherlands.  It was the first Japanese ship that 
crossed the Pacific Ocean.  In 1860, to complete the conclusion of the 
Japan-US Treaty of Amity and Commerce, Kanrin-maru departed from the 
Port of Shinagawa on January 13th.
	Kanrin-maru arrived in the Port of San Francisco on February 
26th.  The captain was Kaishuu Katsu and the interpreter was Manjirou 
John.  On the outbound voyage, bad weather caused Japanese crew to be 
sea-sick.  Americans took over piloting.
	In 1867, the steam of Kanrin-maru was removed.  It became a 
cargo ship.  After the Meiji period, the new Meiji government owned the 
ship.  It sank during a heavy storm in September 1871, off the coast of 
Kikonai.
	At the time, the ship was carring 401 immigrants from Shiroishi 
Castle in the Sendai Domain to Hokkaidou.  No one died in the the 
shipwreck.
  
#3  Hokkaidou Shinkansen opened in 2016.  It is operated by JR 
Hokkaidou.  In the same year, the Esashi Line changed to the Dou-nan 
Isaribi Railway.  The operation was transferred from JR Hokkaidou to 
South Hokkaidou Railway Company (Dou-nan-isaribi-tetsudou). 
	The Esashi Line ran along the Tsugaru Strait.  It connected Go-
ryou-kaku Station in Hakodate City and Kikonai Station.  In the past, 
the Esashi Line entered mountains from Kikonai Town and leached to 
Esashi Town on the sea of Japan side.
	In 2012, Kikonai High School was closed.  In 2014, a section 
between Kikonai Station and Esashi Station on the Esashi Line closed. 
High school students are the main users of local railways.  Part of the 
abolished Esashi Line was converted to a trolley line for sightseeing.
	Kikonai Station on Hokkaidou Shinkansen is also the terminal of 
the Kaikyou Line.  The word ``kaikyou'' means ``strait'' in Japanese.  
The Kakyou Line runs through the undersea Seikan Tunnel.  After the 
opening of the Hokkaidou Shinkansen, only freight trains and special 
trains for group tours use the Kaikyou Line.
	The Hokkaidou Shinkansen uses the same undersea tunnel, 
however, the Shinkansen is not categorized as the Kaikyou line.  The 
track gauge (distance between two rails) is different between the 
Shinkansen and conventional railways including the Kaikyou Line.
	The Seikan Tunnel was made as a dual-gauge (three rails) and 
double-truck railway.  It means that there are six rails in the tunnel. 
	The Shinkansen (bullet train) is standard gauge (1,435 
millimeters).  Conventional railways are narrow gauge (1,067 
millimeters).  Narrow gauge is cheaper to build.
	[See Fukushima Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for the undersea 
tunnel.]
	The former Matsumae Line connected Kikonai Station and Matsumae 
Station.  The railway was abolished in 1988.  It was two years after 
the privatization of JNR (Japanese National Railways, ``Kokutetsu''). 
In the past, there were JNR-branded ashtrays in all passenger cars. 
They were made of thick steel and had a nice sound.
	There were many railways and their branch routes in Hokkaidou.  
In the past, many politicians promised many railways.

#4  Kikonai was a transportation hub in the Matsumae Peninsula. 
Woodworking factories were located near Kikonai Station.
	In the past, even television sets were made from wooden boards. 
Today, in Japanese offices, all desks and chairs are made of steel.
(My office is like a used book store whose space is occupied by steel 
shelves.)
	When I had a zoom meeting with a professor in Vietnam, I found 
a wooden desk and wooden door in the office.  When I visited a 
professor in Sao Paulo, Brazil, I also found a wooden desk, wooden 
chairs, and a wooden book shelf in the office.  I liked them.  

#5  As for dairy farming in Kikonai, in 1897 (Meiji 30), a milk 
collection facility was built.  Horse-drawn carriage transported raw 
milk to Toubetsu Trappist Monastery.  In 1919 (Taishou 8), condensed 
milk butter (``ren-nyuu'' butter) was produced in Kikonai.
	[See Hokuto City in Oshima sub-prefecture for the monastery.  
See Eniwa City in Ishikari sub-prefecture for dairy farming.]
