LOCATION

Hokuto [ho-ku-to] [\u5317\u6597] is a city in Oshima sub-prefecture, 
south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').  The area faces Hakodate Bay and the 
Tsugaru Strait.  The Moheji River, the Oono River, and the Kunebetsu 
River flow.

NAME

The name ``Hokuto'' is Japanese.  It means the Big Dipper that shines 
in the northern sky.  It was named by public offering when Kamiiso 
[\u4E0A\u78EF] Town and Oono [\u5927\u91CE] Town were merged in 2006.  
#1

HISTORY

In the mid 15th century, Mobetsu-date [da-te] (a fort) was built near 
the mouth of the Moheji River.  It was one of the former 12 forts built 
by the Andou clan.  During the Edo era, the area was ruled by the 
Matsumae Domain. 
	[See Kaminokuni Town in Esashi sub-prefecture for the former 12 
forts built in south Hokkaidou.]
	After the Meiji period, in 1880 (Meiji 13), an administrative 
office (``kochou-yakuba'') was established for Oono and other five 
villages.  An administrative office was established for Kamiiso 
and four villages.
	In 1885 (Meiji 18), an administrative office was established 
for Moheji [\u8302\u8FBA\u5730] and another village (Ishibetsu 
[\u77F3\u5225]).  In 1900 (Meiji 33), Kamiiso Village (1st-class 
municipality) and Oono Village (1st-class municipality) were 
established.  
	In 1906 (Meiji 39), Mobetsu [\u8302\u5225] Village (2nd-class 
municipality) was established by the merger of Moheji and Ishibetsu 
villages.  In 1918 (Taishou 7), Kamiiso Town was established.  In 1955 
(Shouwa 30), Kamiiso Town merged Mobetsu Village.  In 1957 (Shouwa 32), 
Oono Town was established.
	[See the note of Matsumae Town for 1st-class and 2nd-class 
municipalities.]

CITY HALL, TRAFFIC, POPULATION

The city hall of Hokuto is located near the mouth of the Oono River.  
It used to be the town hall of Kamiiso Town.  National Route 228 
(Fukuyama-kaidou) and the Dou-nan Isaribi Railway run along Hakodate 
Bay.  #2
	[See Kikonai Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for the Dou-nan 
Isaribi Railway.  See Fukushima Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for 
Fukuyama-kaidou.]
 	The population of Hokuto City increased.  In the southern part 
of the municipality, residential, commercial, and manufacturing areas 
are continued from the center of Hakodate City. 
	In the northern part, National Route 227 (Oono-kokudou) runs 
through the Oono Plain.  The national highway crosses the ridge and 
leads to Esashi Town.  Shin-hakodate-hokuto Station on the Hokkaidou 
Shinkansen is located near the border with Nanae Town.  It used to be 
Oshima-oono Station on the Hakodate Main Line.   

INDUSTRY

Distinctive industries in Hokuto are manufacturing, agriculture, and 
fishery.  STATISTICS OF AGRICULTURE = paddy rice 1,198 hectares in 
2015, fodder 659, beans (soybeans 239, adzuki beans 9, other beans 5), 
green onions 131, pasture 110, radishes 57, tomatoes 50, potatoes 39, 
spinach 37, cabbage 28, Chinese cabbage 16, lettuce 14, cucumbers 14, 
	(continued) --> orchards 11, strawberries 9, yams 6, flowers 4, 
onions 2, other vegetables 139+X, other grains 8, and other fruits 1; 
dairy cows 336 head in 2015.  STATISTICS OF FISHERIES = salmon 387 tons 
in 2017, anchovy 242, yellowtail 88, 
	(continued) --> shellfish (abalone 1, Manila clam 1, other 
