	On the satellite image, a straight line stretches from Hokuto 
City to Hakodate Bay.  The line is a jetty of Taiheiyou Cement's 
Kamiiso Factory.  The limestone deposit for the cement industry was 
discovered in 1872 by Benjamin Smith Lyman.  Lyman was an American 
mining scholar invited by the Meiji government.  #3
	Paddy rice cultivation started in Oono district in the late 
17th century.  It was the first rice cultivation in Hokkaidou.  #4
	As for sightseeing, the building printed on the country sign 
(gateway sign) is Toubetsu Trappist Monastery.  The monastery is 
located to the west, near the border with Kikonai Town.  The old red-
brick buildings and tree-lined avenues are famous.  #5

NOTE 

#1  The former Kamiiso Town was located along Hakodate Bay.  The name 
``Kamiiso'' was derived from Kamiiso county, which was established in 
1869 (Meiji 2).  The county's name was suggestion by Takeshirou 
Matsuura, who explored Ezo (now Hokkaidou) in the Edo era.
	The name ``Kami-iso'' is Japanese.  It means ``upper, coast.'' 
The word ``upper'' refers to the west, where the castle of the 
Matsumae Domain was located.
	In the Edo era, the area of the former Kamiiso Town was 
Arukawa village and Hekerechi village.  The names were documented in 
Matsumae Island Village Record (Matsumae-tou-gou-chou) published in 
1700.  Today, in Hokuto City, there are Arikawa-dai-jinguu Shrine and 
the Hekirichi River.
	[See Hakodate City in Oshima sub-prefecture for Matsumae 
Island Village Record.]
	The former Oono Town was located inland.  The name ``Oo-no'' is 
Japanese, which means ``large, plain.''   The name ``Oono'' is old, 
which was documented in Matsjmae Island Village Record (Matsumae-tou-
gou-chou) published in 1700.
	* * *
	Takeshirou Matsuura may have derived the name ``Kamiiso'' from 
Kamiiso-kaidou (Kamiiso trail) in Tsugaru (now Aomori Prefecture).
	Kamiiso-kaidou was called Matsumae-kaidou.  It connected Abura-
kawa (now part of Aomori City) and Min-maya (now part of Sotoga-hama 
Town, Aomori Prefecture).  Min-maya was a port for heading to Matsumae.
	Takeshirou Matsuura also suggested Hiyama county and Tsugaru 
county in Hokkaidou.  Those names (Kamiiso, Hiyama, and Tsugaru) are 
related to the places in the Touhoku Region that have historical 
connections to Hokkaidou.
	The trail that connects Matsumae and Hakodate was called 
Fukuyama-kaidou (Fukuyama trail).  Fukuyama was the castle town of the 
Matsumae Domain.
	[See Fukushima Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for Fukuyama-
kaidou.]
 
#2  I traveled on National Route 228 (Fukuyama-kaidou) on a bus 
excursion.  I saw many concrete wave-breaking blocks along the coast 
of Hokuto.  Hokuto is one of the largest cement producing 
municipalities in the country.
	Wave-breaking blocks are known as Tetrapods.  The name was the 
patent of Neyrpic, a French company.  I heard this story from Professor 
Tsuguo Sunamura at University of Tsukuba in 1995 (HTTP://2242.MOOO.COM/
POSI/95IZU/1452.JPG INDEX.HTM); 
 	``When executives of Neyrpic visited Japan, they found many 
fake Tetrapods along the coast.  Then, Nippon Tetrapod, a branch of 
Neyrpic, was established in 1961.
	The fake Tetrapods in Japan had metal hooks.  They were easy to 
install, however, they were less durable.  The metal hook corrodes.''

#3  As for cement industry in Hokuto City, Taiheiyou Cement Kamiiso 
Factory extracts limestone at Garou Mine.  The cement is transported to 
cargo ships via a long jetty.  The length is two kilometers.  The jetty
makes a long line on the map.
 	In 1884 (Meiji 17), a cement factory was established.  In 1890 
(Meiji 23), Hokkaidou Cement was established.  In 1915 (Taishou 4), 
Asano Cement acquired Hokkaidou Cement.
	After World War II, Asano zaibatsu was dismantled. 
(``Zaibatsu'' was a large conglomerate.)  Asano Cement changed its name 
to Nihon Cement.  In 1988 (Shouwa 63), Taiheiyou Cement was established 
by the merger of Nihon Cement and Chichibu Onoda Cement.  The product 
name ``Asano Cement'' was used until 1998. 
	Concrete is made from cement.  Cement is made from limestone, 
gravel, and water.  Limestone is self-sufficient in the small country.
Cities are like concrete jungles.  Limestone mountains are like 
skeletons.
	* * *
	Today, almost all electric poles are made of concrete. The 
oldest concrete electric pole is still used in Hakodate City.  It was 
installed in 1923 (Taishou 12) to prevent it from burning by fire.  (I 
like old wooden electric poles, although tourist destinations remove 
electricity poles nowadays.)

#4  The former Oono Town is the birth place of paddy rice cultivation 
in Hokkaidou.  It started in the Edo era.  There is a stone monument 
that commemorates the first paddy rice.  The inscription reads; 
	``In 1692, a farmer Sakuemon opened a paddy filed of 450 tsubo 
(0.15 hectares) using natural water and gained rice of 10-hyou.'' (One 
``hyou'' of rice is 60 kg.)
 	That record was excellent at the time. Today, a good paddy 
field that has a yield of 600 kg per 0.1 hectares.  Such paddy is 
called ``jippyo-dori (10-hyou gaining paddy).''
	According to oral tradition, paddy rice cultivation in the 
former Oono Town dates back to the Kanbun period (1661-1672) and 1685.
[By Yoshiaki Ishizuka & Tatsuzou Hoshino eds. 1994.  ``Hokkaidou-no-
inasaku [Rice cultivation of Hokkaidou].''  Hokunoukai.]
	Kametarou Ootomo was an engineer in the Edo era.  He instructed 
agriculture in Oono village (now Oono district in Hokuto City).  In 
1866, at the end of the Edo era, he moved to Sapporo with villagers 
and started developing the area.
