LOCATION

Hakodate [ha-ko-da-te] [\u51FD\u9928] is a city in Oshima sub-
prefecture, south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').  The area faces Hakodate 
Bay, Tsugaru Strait, and the Pacific Ocean.  It occupies the southeast 
of the Oshima Peninsula.  This part of the Oshima Peninsula is called 
the Kameda Peninsula. 
	Mt. Hakodate stands from Hakodate Bay.  The height is 334 
meters.  (Tokyo Tower is 333 meters.)  The area of Hakodate was newly 
formed in 2004 by the merger of Hakodate City, Toi Town, Minami-kayabe 
Town, Esan Town, and Todohokke Village.  #1  #2  #3 

NAME

The name ``Hako-date'' means ``box, fort'' in Japanese.  It referred to 
the box-like shape of a fort.  The fort was Usukeshi-date, which was 
run by the Kouno clan after 1454.  The Kouno clan was one of the 
vassals of the Andou clan, who built 12 forts in what is now south 
Hokkaidou.

HISTORY

Koshamain's War occurred in 1457.  Koshamain was a chief of Ainu 
people.  During the war, Usukeshi-date, so-called Hako-date, was 
destroyed by the Ainu forces.
	[See Kaminokuni Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for the Andou 
clan and Koshamain's War.]
	In the Edo era, the Port of Hakodate was managed by the 
Matsumae Domain and later by the Tokugawa Shogunate.  The port opened 
for American ships in 1854 under the Convention of Kanagawa (Japan-US 
Treaty of Peace and Amity).  #4
 	In the beginning of the Meiji period, Hakodate was the battle 
ground of the Boshin War (1868-1869).  In 1869 (Meiji 2), the Hokkaidou 
Development Commission was established.  In 1871, the head office 
of the Hokkaidou Development Commission moved to Sapporo.  #5
	In 1879 (Meiji 12), Hakodate ward (Hakodate-ku [\u533A]) was 
established.  This ``ward'' was an administrative district, not a 
municipality.  In 1899 (Meiji 32), Hakodate Ward was established.  
This ``Ward'' was a municipality (local government).
	In 1922 (Taishou 11), Hakodate City was established.  In 1939 
(Shouwa 14), Hakodate City merged Yunokawa [\u6E6F\u5DDD] Town (1st-
class municipality).  Yunokawa Town was located around Yunokawa Hot 
Spring.
	[See Kushiro Town in Kushiro sub-prefecture for Wards (``ku'') 
in Hokkaidou.  See the note of Matsumae Town for 1st-class 
municipality.]
	In 1966 (Shouwa 41), Hakodate City merged Zenigame-zawa [\u92AD
\u4E80\u6CA2] Village (the former 1st-class municipality).  Zenigame-
zawa was located around Hakodate Airport.  In 1973 (Shouwa 48), 
Hakodate City merged Kameda [\u4E80\u7530] City.  #6

CITY HALL, TRAFFIC, PULATION
  
The city hall of Hakodate and the Port of Hakodate are located at the 
foot of Mt. Hakodate.  National Route 5 and the Hakodate Main Line 
start from the port.
	Hakodate was the gateway to Japan in the late 19th century, 
during the Edo era.  Hakodate was the gateway to Hokkaidou from the 
late 19th century to the late 20th century.
	The Seikan Train Ferry (Seikan-renraku-sen) connected Hakodate 
and Aomori.  The name ``Sei-kan'' is an abbreviation of Aomori and 
Hakodate in Kanji characters.  #7
	The population peaked in 1980 at 345,165 (including 
municipalities of Hakodate, Toi, Esan, Minami-kayabe, and Todohokke). 
The population decreased. The reasons are (1) the end of pelagic 
fishing (deep-sea fishing), (2) opening of the Seikan Tunnel, (3) an 
increase in air travelers, and (4) motorization and suburbanization.  
#8

