	Go-ryou-kaku Castle was built inland to avoid artillery from 
foreign ships.  In 1854, the Tokugawa Shogunate singed the Japan-US 
Treaty of Peace and Amity.  From 1857 to 1866, they constructed Go-ryou
-kaku.  Go-ryou-kaku became the last castle of the Tokugawa Shogunate 
forces.  It fell in the Boshin War.
	Today, tourists enjoy climbing up an observation tower in 
front of the castle.  The height of the tower is 100 meters.  Visitors 
can look down on the pentagonal shape of the castle.  The name ``Go-
ryou-kaku'' is Japanese.  It means ``five, point, fort.''  Cannons 
could be placed at the points. 
	In Hakodate, Western-style buildings that were built in the 
Meiji period has been preserved, for example, Hokkaidou Government 
Hakodate Branch Office and Hakodate Ward Public Hall. They were 
constructed after the great fires in the Meiji period.  #11
	At Ekini market, tourists can enjoy squid fishing.  The squid 
they catch is eaten on the spot.  Ekini market used to be a morning 
fair in front of Hakodate Station.  #12

