meters, because guns were placed.  Mt. Hakodate was a military base 
from the Meiji period to the Shouwa period (before Wold War II).
	Some people say that the nature of Mt. Hakodate remains, 
because only military personnel entered the mountain.  However, after 
the fort called Hako-date was built in the 15th century, people cut 
down native trees.  In the past, trees were used not only as building 
materials but also as energy (firewood).
	Today, cedar trees can be seen along the tourist road of Mt. 
Hakodate.  Buses go on the road and a ropeway runs above it.  The ceder 
trees have been cultivated since the Edo era (about 200 years ago).
