	Japanese isolation policy was ended due to the effort 
(pressure) of Matthew Perry, who was the commander of the East India 
Squadron in the United States.
	On his black steamships (``kuro-fune''), Matthew Perry appeared 
in many ports in Japan after 1853.  The flagship was Susquehanna.  
Japanese people were surprised at the black ships, which moved by steam 
engine.  At the time, sail ships were moved by the wind.
	[See Takikawa City in Sorachi sub-prefecture for steamers.]
	In 1859, the Treaty of Amity and Commerce between Japan and the 
United States (Nichi-bei-syuukou-tsuushou-jouyaku) was concluded.  It 
was concluded between the Tokugawa Shogunate and the United States.  
	Then, along with Hakodate, the ports of Kanagawa (Yokohama), 
Nagasaki, Hyougo (Koube), and Niigata were opened.  The Port of Shimoda 
was closed instead of Kanagawa.
	Foreign settlements were built near the ports.  Cities of Edo 
(now the center of Tokyo) and Oosaka were opened for foreign visitors.  
  
