	The last stop on the tram is Yunokawa Hot Spring.  It is Oku-
zashiki of Hakodate (so-called the inner parlor of Hakodate.)  Yunokawa 
Hot spring was opened by the Matsumae Domain in 1653.  In the hot 
spring, there was a nice and inexpensive hotel, which we stayed during 
excursions.  Today, it is difficult to stay at the hotel, because it 
became popular with foreign tourists.  It became expensive.
	* * *
	Local foods of Hakodate include Lucky Pierrot hamburgers, 
Madalena cookies from Trappistine Monastery, curry and rice, and the 
grilled-chicken lunch-box of Hasegawa Store.
	The restaurant Gotou-ken opened in the Meiji period.  It became 
popular for its curry and rice.  Nowadays, tourists like to eat curry 
and rice even in the morning at hotel buffets.
	As for Lucky Pierrot hamburgers; (1) It is popular than 
McDonald in Hakodate City, (2) It serves whale hamburgers, (3) It 
serves large hambergers, and (4) The shops are located near high 
schools.  The Food in port cities are hearty and delicious.
	[See Kushiro City in Kushiro sub-prefecture and Nemuro City in 
Nemuro sub-prefecture for the food in port cities.]
	* * *
	Curry was brought to Japan via the British Navy.  The original 
place of curry and rice is India.  It was the vassal state of the 
British Empire.  Naval cities in Japan such as Yokosuka and Sasebo 
appeal their curry and rice.
	Indian curry is like a soup.  Japanese curry is like a sauce, 
because naval crews ate it on traveling warships.  In Hokkaidou, curry 
was introduced not only in Hakodate but also in Sappro.  Curry and rice 
were served for American teachers and Japanese students at Sapporo 
Agricultural College.
	[See Hokkaidou University in Kita Ward, Sapporo City, Ishikari 
sub-prefecture, for curry and rice.]
	* * * 
 	Curry is basically a soup.  If a family serves curry and 
``miso'' (soybean paste) soup at the dinner, they retain an old custom. 
Curry and rice has been eaten by Japanese people for a long time.  In 
the past, farmers had many children.  Children were hungry and liked 
curry and rice.  Mothers cooked ``miso'' soup and curry so that all 
family members could eat curry.
	Brazilian people ate ``feijoada (soup of black beans and 
intestines)'' on Saturdays and Wednesdays.  Japan people ate curry 
and rice on Saturdays.  Those dishes provided stamina.  They were 
special dishes for laborers.  (I ate leftover curry on Sundays.)
	* * *
	There is a TV drama ``Shin-ya-shokudou (Midnight Dinner).'' One 
story features about butter rice and Hakodate City.  Butter rice is 
rice topped with butter and soy sauce.  
	Professor Tooru Ikeda at Faculty of Letters, Hokkaidou 
University, also recommended butter rice.  He was from Hokkaidou. 
Butter rice is popular in Hokkadou.  http://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/
%E3%83%90%E3%82%BF%E3%83%BC%E3%81%94%E9%A3%AF
