LOCATION

Nanae [na-na-e] [\u4E03\u98EF] is a town in Oshima sub-prefecture, 
south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').  Nanae is an inland town.  The Kunebetsu 
River flows south and empties into Hakodate Bay.
	Mt. Komagatake (1,131 meters, volcano) rises to the north. 
Lake Oonuma is located at the foot of Mt. Komagatake.  Lake Oonuma and 
Mt. Komgatake are designated as Oonuma Quasi National Park (Oonuma-
kokutei-kouen).

NAME

The name ``Nanae'' comes from ``naa-nay'' in Ainu language, which means 
``many, stream.''  Or, it comes from ``nam-nay'' in Ainu language, 
which means ``cold, stream.''  Both signified Nanae-hama beach along 
Hakodate Bay.
	Nanae-hama beach now belongs to Hokuto City.  Nanae has a long 
history of Japanese immigration, so the origin of the name is vague.
	Nanae Town belongs to Kameda county.  The name ``Kame-da'' 
means ``turtle, paddy.''  It is a good-luck name.
	[See Hakodate City in Oshima sub-prefecture for the name 
``Kameda.''] 

HISTORY

Before the Edo era, Mishima Shrine was built in 1532.  It was around 
the time that a Japanese village was established.  When a Japanese 
village was established, a shrine was also established.  [By Nihei lab 
2023-2025b.]
	In the Edo era (from the early 17th centry to the mid 19th 
century), Nanae [\u4E03\u91CD] was a Japanese village.  It was 
governed by the Matsumae Domain.
	After the Meiji period, in 1870 (Meiji 3), Nanae Kan-en 
(government farm) was established by the Hokkaidou Development 
Commission.  An American advisor Edwin Dun instructed Western-style 
farming at the government farm, including dairy farming and butter 
production.  #1
  	In 1879 (Meiji 12), the administrative office (``kochou-
yakuba'') of Nanae [\u4E03\u98EF] village was established by the merger 
of Nanae and Iida [\u98EF\u7530].
	In the same year, the administrative office of Oonakayama 
[\u5927\u4E2D\u5C71] village was established by the merger of Ookawa 
[\u5927\u5DDD] and Nakajima [\u4E2D\u5CF6].
 	In 1885 (Meiji 18), Nanae village merged Oonakayama village.  
In 1902 (Meiji 35), Nanae Village (2nd-class municipality) was 
established.  Nanae Station on Hokkaidou Railway (now the Hakodate Main 
Line) opened.
	In 1907 (Meiji 40), Nanae Village (1st-class municipality) was 
established.  In 1957 (Shouwa 32), Nanae Town was established.
	[See the note of Matsumae Town for 1st-class and 2nd-class 
municipalities.]

TOWN HALL, TRAFFIC, POPULATION

The town hall of Nanae is located on the south of the Hakodate Plain.  
The part of the plain is called Oono Plain.  National Route 5 (Oonuma-
kokudou) and the Hakodate Main Line run through the plain.  The part of 
National Route 5 with Akamatsu-namiki (row of red pine trees)  is 
designated as one of the 100 Roads of Japan.  #2  #3  #4
	The south part of Nanae Town is a built-up area that continues 
from Hakodate City.  The part includes Oonakayama Station on the 
Hakodate Main Line.  The population of Nanae Town increased.  Nanae is 
the second largest town (``machi'') in Hokkaidou.  (The largest is 
Otofuke Town in Tokachi sub-prefecture.)

INDUSTRY

Distinctive industries in Nanae are manufacturing, agriculture, dairy 
farming, and sightseeing.  The main manufacturing products are soft 
drinks (including Guarana [Guaran\u00E1]), wine, and semiconductors.  
STATISTICS OF AGRICULTURE = pasture 669 hectares in 2015, paddy rice 
400, fodder 280, carrots 210, green onions 114, radishes 89, 
	(continued) --> orchards 60, flowers 22 (carnations and other 
flowers), spinach 18, beans (soybeans 9, adzuki beans 4, other beans 
4), tomatoes 11, cabbage 8, cucumbers 8, onions 3, broccoli 3, 
 	(continued) --> apples X (concealed), other vegetables 91+X 
(sweet corn, pumpkins, asparagus), and other grains 3; dairy cows 1,988 
head in 2015 and hens 12,800.  #5
	As for sightseeing, Oonuma has been designated as the New 
Three Scenic Views of Japan.  Niyama Ski Ground is located next to 
Niyama Station.  #6  #7  #8

NOTE
 
#1  As for Nanae Governmental Farm, in 1863, the Gaertner brothers 
rented the land and started Western-style farming.  They came from 
Prussia (now Germany).  The area of their farm was 990 hectares.  Cf. 
Hokkaidou University Ranch is 470 hectares.
	[See Shin-hidaka Town in Hidaka sub-prefecture for Hokkaidou 
Univeristy Ranch.] 
	The Gaertner brothers primarily engaged in trade and 
consulship.  They also cultivated apples, pears, gooseberries, 
cherries, and vegetables.  The apples were the first Western varieties 
cultivated in Japan.  The brothers taught Western-style farming to 
neighboring farmers.
	The Gaertner brothers sold food to foreign ships in the Port of 
Hakodate.  There are no photographs or paintings of the brothers.
 	The brothers planted beech trees.  The trees became a forest 
along National Route 5.  Beech trees were used for grazing pigs 
in their home country.  Beech trees have acorns.  (The meat of the wild 
boars [``inoshishi] that ate acorns is good.)
 	In 1870 (Meiji 3), the Gaertner brothers' farm was closed.  On 
the site, Nanae Government Farm (Nanae-kan-en) opened.  The Meiji 
government bought the land back.
	To introduce Western-style farming to Hokkaidou, the Meiji 
government established five government farms in Tokyo and Hokkaidou.  
The locations were Aoyama and Azabu in Tokyo, and Nanae, Sapporo, and 
Nemuro in Hokkaidou.  Among them, Nanae Government Farm was the 
largest.
	An English writer Isabella Lucy Bird visited Nanae Government 
Farm in 1878.  She reported the scenery like this; ``The farm looked 
like a Western country.  It had Western-style buildings such as animal 
stables, a large watermill, and a butter factory.''
	[See Mori Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for Isabella Lucy 
Bird.]
	In 1882, the Hokkaidou Development Commission was abolished. 
Nanae Government Farm was gradually sold off and closed in 1894.  Only 
its stone wall remains near Nanae Elementary School.
 
#2  Mt. Nanae (779 meters) rises near the town hall of Nanae.  The 
night view of Hakodate from Mt. Nanae is called Hakodate-ura-yakei 
(another side of Hakodate night view).

#3  Oonuma Station on the Hakodate Main Line is a junction between 
Oonuma main route and Sawara branch route.  Another branch route exists 
between Oonuma Station and Nanae Station.  It is Fujishiro branch 
route, which was built by Japanese National Railways in 1966 to 
increasing transport capacity.  It was planned before motorization.
	[See Mori Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for Sawara branch 
route.  See the note of Otobe Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for 
motorization.]

#4  Red pine trees (``aka-matsu'') along National Route 5 are large.  
They ere reminiscent of old trails in Honshuu island.  In 1876 (Meiji 
9), the red pine trees were transplanted from Go-ryou-kaku Castle to 
the roadside.
	 The purpose of transplantation was to make a scenic road 
before Emperor Meiji visited Nanae Government Farm.  Cf. Cherry trees 
along Nijikken Road were also transplanted to welcome the Emperor.  
	[See Uryuu Town in Sorachi sub-prefecture for red pine trees.  
See Shin-hidaka Town in Hidaka sub-prefecture for Nijjikken Road.]
 
#5  During lectures at Hokkaidou University, some students are drinking
Guarana.  Guarana [Guaran\u00E1] is a popular drink in Brazil.  It is 
like Brazilian Coca-cola.
	Guarana is made from the berries of Guarana trees.  The berries 
are small and red.  Guarana trees are native to the Amazon region, 
which includes the world's largest tropical rainforest.
	After World War II, Coca-cola became popular in Honshuu island. 
Before the American product landed in Hokkaidou island, a company in 
Nanane started to produce and sell Guarana.  It is still popular in 
Hokkaidou.
	During a lecture, when I saw a student drinking a can of 
Guarana, I would tell this story;
	``Japanese people pronounce Guarana as `ga-ra-na.'  It is like 
English.  In Brazil, the original place of Guarana, people pronounce it 
`gu-a-ra-na.'  It is like Latin.
	When I ordered Guarana in a jet plane in Brazil, I said `Ah, 
ga-ra-na.'  Then, the stewardess gave me a bottle of water.  It may 
have sounded `Agua, ne?' (Water, OK?).''
 
#6  These are the New Three Scenic Views of Japan; Mihono-matsubara in 
Shizuoka Prefecture (Honshuu island), Yabakei in Ooita Prefecture 
(Kyuushuu island), and Oonuma in Hokkaidou Prefecture (Hokkaidou 
island).  They were designated in 1915 (Taishou 4).
	(Nowadays, they are not new.  Japanese people like putting 
``new'' to things.  They also like ``top-three things.'')
	The original Three Scenic Views are located in Honshuu island. 
They are Matsushima in Miyagui Prefecture (Pacific Ocean), Amano-
hashidate in Kyouto Prefecture (the Sea of Japan), and Itsukushima in 
Hiroshima Prefecture (the Seto Inland Sea).
	The original Three Scenic Views were selected in 1643, during 
the Edo era.  At the time, the Tokugawa Shogunate ruled the country and 
ordinary people could not travel freely.

#7  Oonuma Quasi National Park includes Lake Oonuma, Lake Konuma, and 
Lake Junsai.  The shapes of the lakes were formed by the eruption of 
Mt. Komagatake in 1640.
	In Lake Oonuma, smelt and shrimp are caught.  In Lake Junsai, 
Junsai (buds of watershield) is harvested.  Junsai is tasty in Dashi 
soup.  Dashi soup is a transparent soup made from Konbu kelp and 
Katsuo-bushi (shaved dried bonito).
	In the end of the Edo era, Lake Oonuma was opened to foreigners 
for walking.  In the Meiji period, an ice factory was built on the 
shore of Lake Oonuma.  The factory cut ice cubes from Lake Oonuma in 
winter.  The ice cubes were stored until summer and shipped from 
Hakodate to Tokyo. [By Professor Katsuhiko Yamashita at the Meeting of 
Hokkaidou Geographical Society in 2014.]
	The story of ice factory reminds me of the etymology of Nanae,
which means ``cold stream.''  Ice was expensive in summer in the past. 
	After the 1960s, villas were developed on the slope from Lake 
Oonuma to Mt. Komagatake.  Aerial photographs show roundabouts and 
``cul-de-sac'' in the area.  (A cul-de-sac is a dead end that has a 
circular shape.)
	In Japanese, there are no difference between roundabout and 
rotary.  Both are called rotary.  I have never seen a roundabout or 
rotary in Honshuu island.  In Canada, I had to drive through 
roundabouts.
	[See Otaru City in Shiribeshi sub-prefecture and Kushiro City 
in Kushiro sub-prefecture for roundabout and rotary.]
	* * *
	The famous song ``Sen-no-kaze-ni-natte (Be Thousand Winds)'' 
was translated by a composer at a villa in Oonuma.  The original 
is an American poem, ``Do not stand at my grave and weep.''  
	The poem continues, ``I am not there, I am the thousand winds 
that blow.''  (I agree.  When I die and become a ghost, I will not be 
in my grave.  I will go to Daimaru department store and watch people.)

#8  This is a legend about Lake Oonuma and Mt. Komagatake; ``Masatane 
Aihara was the load of Fort Oodate in the 15th century.  The fort was 
located in what is now Matsumae Town.  Masatane Aihara came to Ezo 
island (now Hokkaidou) with Masasue Andou, Kakizaki Sueshige, and 
Nobuhiro Takeda.
	Masatne Andou was the leader of them.  He built 12 forts in Ezo 
island and returned to the main island.  Nobuhiro Takeda ended 
Koshamain's war and inherited the Kakizaki clan.  He changed his name 
to Nobuhiro Kakizaki and started to rule Ezo island.
	Masatane Aihara came into conflict with Nobuhiro Kakizaki. 
Masatane Aihara was defeated and fled to Lake Oonuma.  He drowned 
himself into the lake.  Later, the Kakizaki clan became the lord of the 
Matsumae Domain in the Edo era (from the 17th to the 19th centuries).
	Even in the Edo era, Masatane Aihara's horse was seen near Lake 
Oonuma.  The horse had a very long mane that reached on the ground.''
	This legend says that the name of Mt. Komagatake signifies the 
Masatane Aihara's ghost horse.  The name ``Koma-ga-take'' means 
``horse, of, mountain'' in Japanese.  It is generally said that the 
shape of the mountain looks like a horse.
	* * *
	The story above is a legend.  Masatane Aihara may have died 
during Koshamain's War.  The story of Aihara remind me of Yoshitsune 
legend.  Yoshitune Minamoto was killed by his elder brother Yoritomo 
Minamoto, who established the Kamakura Shogunate.
	Japanese people feel sympathy for tragic heroes.  The sympathy 
is called Hangan-biiki (or Hougan-biiki).  The word ``Hangan'' means 
the job position of Yoshitsune Minamoto.  The word ``hiiki (biiki)'' 
means sympathy.
	[See Kaminokuni Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for the old 12 
forts established by the Andou clan.  See Biratori Town in Hidaka sub-
prefecture for Yoshitsune legend.  See Niikappu Town in Hidaka sub-
prefecture for Hangan-date Rock.]
