LOCATION

Shikabe [shi-ka-be] [\u9E7F\u90E8] is a town in Oshima sub-prefecture, 
south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').  The Orito River and the Tokoro River 
flow into the Pacific Ocean.  The Orito River flows from Lake Oonuma in 
Oonuma Quasi National Park.
	Mt. Komagatake (1,131 meters, volcano) stands to the north.  It 
erupted in 1929.  A large amount of pumice piled up.
	[See Nanae Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for Mt. Komagatake and 
Lake Oonuma.]

NAME

The name ``Shikabe'' comes from ``sikerpe'' in Ainu language. It means 
``Amur cork tree.''  (Amur cork is called ``Kihada'' in Japanese.)
	Or, it comes from ``sike-un-pe'' in Ainu language, which means 
``carry, it, place.''  The latter signified a place where Ainu people 
got off their boats and carried their luggage.  Both signified the 
mouth of the Shikabe River.  #1

HISTORY

In 1666, during the Edo era, a hot spring was discovered by Guen-gorou 
Itou, who came from Tsugaru (now Aomori Prefecture).  He found a deer 
(``shika'') that healed its wounds in the hot spring.  It 
is the origin of Shikabe Hot Spring.  In the Edo era, fishermen 
migrated from Nanbu (now Aomori Prefecture).
 	After the Meiji period, in 1879 (Meiji 12), the administrative 
office (``kochou-yakuba'') of Shikabe village was established.  In 1906 
(Meiji 39), Shikabe Village (2nd-class municipality) was established. 
In 1983 (Shouwa 58), Shikabe Town was established.
	[See the note of Matsumae Town for 2nd-class municipality.]

TOWN HALL, TRAFFIC

The town hall of Shikabe is located near the mouth of the 
Shikabe River.  National Route 278 (Esan-kokudou) runs.  At the foot of 
Mt. Komagatake, Sawara branch route of the Hakodate Main Line runs.  It 
runs along the Pacific coast, avoiding the slope of Mt. Komagatake. 

INDUSTRY

Distinctive industries in Shikabe are fishery and tourism.  STATISTICS 
OF AGRICULTURE = pasture 52 hectares in 2015 and fodder 16; dairy cows 
- (zero) head in 2015. STATISTICS OF FISHERIES = walleye pollock 4,165 
tons in 2017, sardines 701, octopus 401, shellfish 327 (including 
scallops), mackerel 146, squid (flying squid 134, other squid 8), 
	(continued) --> right-eye flounder 125, yellowtail 95, Konbu 
kelp 89, salmon 75, Pacific cod 55, sea urchins 47, tuna 11, atka 
mackerel 7, Hatahata 7, olive flounder 4, shrimp/prawns 4, herring 4, 
Kichiji 4, sea trout 3, horse mackerel 2, other fish 108+X (concealed), 
and other marine animals 62.
 	Fishing ports are located in Shikabe, Honbetsu, and Dekima 
districts.  As for sightseeing, cottages, golf courses, and a resort 
hotel are located near Shikabe Station.  (Shikabe Station is far from 
the center of the town.)
	Shikabe Roadside Station (Michino-eki-shikabe) is located on 
National Route 278.  There is a geyser that gushes hot water up to 15 
meters.  It is a part of Shikabe Hot Spring.  #2
 
NOTE
 
#1  As for the name ``Shikabe,'' which means Amur cork tree in Ainu 
language, Amur cork tree was used as a yellow dye and as an intestinal 
medicine.  Amur cork tree is called ``Ki-hada'' in Japanese.  It means 
``yellow, skin.''
	Large Amur cork trees grow on the central lawn of Hokkaidou 
University.  In 2018, during Typhoon No. 21, their large branches were 
fell.  The yellow color of their barks stood out.
 	Ainu people made ritual sticks (``inau'') from branches of 
these trees; Kihada, Yanagui (willow), Mizuki (dogwood), and Enju 
(pagoda tree).  Ainu people believe that those trees have good spirits.
	Ainu's ritual sticks can be found in Hokkaidou University.  The 
location is the Forest of Archaeological Site.  There used to be Ainu 
villages in the forest.  Ainu's ritual sticks look like dread hair. 
Japanese people make ritual sticks from Sakaki (broad-leaved evergreen 
tree).  
	[See Abashiri City in Okhotsk sub-prefecture for Enju tree.  
See Biratori Town in Hidaka sub-prefecture for Ainu culture.  See Nihei 
lab 2023-2025b for Sakaki tree.]
 
#2  As for Shiakbe Station on the Hakodate Main Line, the former name 
was Takamachi Station.  There was Shikabe Station on the Oonuma-
dentetsu Line.  Oonuma-dentetsu Line ran between 1929 and 1952 along 
the Orito River.  After the abolition of the Oonuma-dentetsu Line, 
Takamachi Station was renamed Shikabe Station.
	The name ``Takamachi'' means ``hawk catcher'' in Japanese. 
During the Edo era, hawk catchers caught hawks and falcons for 
falconry.
	[See Shiriuchi Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for falconry.]
