LOCATION

Mori [mo-ri] [\u68EE] is a town in Oshima sub-prefecture, south 
Hokkaidou (Dou-nan).  The area faces Uchiura Bay (Volcano Bay).  The 
Nigorikawa River, the Torizaki River, and the Oshironai River flow.  
	Mt. Komagatake (1,131 meters, volcano) rises to the south.  The 
area was newly established by the merger of Mori Town and Sawara Town 
in 2005.  #2

NAME

The name ``Mori'' means ``forest'' in Japanese.  The original name was 
Oniushi.  The name ``Oniushi'' comes from ``o-ni-us-pet'' in Ainu 
language.  It means ``river mouth, tree, many, river.''  It signified 
the Torizaki River or the Mori River.
	The pronunciation of Oni-ushi sounds like ``demon, ox'' in 
Japanese.  Japanese immigrants may not have liked the name and 
translated.

HISTORY

In the 16th century, the first Japanese immigrants came from Tsugaru 
(now Aomori Prefecture).  In the Edo era, Kayabe-basho (a trading 
place) was established.  It was managed by the Matsumae Domain for 
herring fishing.  Nigorikawa Hot Spring opened in 1805 in Nigorikawa 
Caldera.  #3 
	Villages of Washinoki, Mori, and Oshironai were established in 
the Edo era.  The following is the history of Mori Town after the Meiji 
period;

OLD MORI TOWN; In 1880 (Meiji 13), an administrative office (``kochou-
yakuba'') was established in Washinoki [\u9DF2\u30CE\u6728] village.  
It covered villages of Ebiya [\u86EF\u8C37] and Ishikura [\u77F3
\u5009].
	In 1881 (Meiji 14), the administrative office of Mori village 
was established.  It covered villages of Oshironai [\u5C3E\u767D\u5185] 
and Shukunobe [\u5BBF\u91CE\u8FBA]. 
	In 1899 (Meiji 22), Mori village merged Washinoki village.  The 
administrative office covered six villages of Mori, Oshironai, 
Shukunobe, Washinoki, Ebiya, and Ishikura.  In 1902 (Meiji 35), Mori 
Village (2nd-class municipality) was established.  #4
	In 1903 (Meiji 36), Mori Station on Hokkaidou Railway (now the 
Hakodate Main Line) opened.  In 1907 (Meiji 40), Mori Village (1st-
class municipality) was established.  In 1921 (Taishou 10), Mori Town 
was established.
	[See the note of Matsumae Town for 1st-class and 2nd-class 
municipalities.]

OLD SAWARA TOWN; In 1880 (Meiji 13), the administrative office 
(``kochou-yakuba'') of Sawara [\u7802\u539F] village was established. 
It covered Kakeruma [\u639B\u6F97] village.  In 1906 (Meiji 39), Sawara 
Village (2nd-class municipality) was established.
	In 1927 (Shouwa 2), Sawara Station on Oshima-kaigan-tetsudou 
(Oshima Coastal Railway) opened.  It was the current Sawara branch 
route of the Hakodate Main Line.  In 1970 (Shouwa 45), Sawara Town was 
established.

TOWN HALL, TRAFFIC
The town hall of Mori is located between the Torizaki River and the 
Mori River.  National Route 278 (Esan-kokudou) branches off from 
National Route 5 (Oonuma-kokudou) near the town hall.  National Route 
278 runs along Uchiura Bay.  #5
	Mori Station on the Hakodate Main Line is the junction of 
Oonuma main route and Sawara branch route.  Heavy freight [furei't] 
trains go the branch route along the bay.  #6

INDUSTRY

Distinctive industries in Mori are fishery, agriculture, animal 
husbandry, food processing, and geothermal power generation.  
