726, other squid 14), mackerel 578, shellfish (scallops [cultured] 161, 
other shellfish 198), octopus 254, salmon 242, shrimp/prawns 169 
(including Botan shrimp), Konbu kelp 164, yellowtail 126, 
	(continued) --> sand lance 71, crabs (snow crabs 44, other 
crabs 26), herring 68, anchovy 31, sharks 28, Pacific cod 27, horse 
mackerel 16, sea urchins 13, tuna 10, puffer fish 6, olive flounder 5, 
atka mackerel 3, sea trout 2, Kichiji 2, Hatahata 2, congers 1, marine 
mammals 2, other fish 481, and other marine animals 66.  #7  #8
	At Nigorikawa district, farmers cultivate Onsen Tomato (hot-
spring tomatoes).  The tomatoes are grown in the greenhouses that are 
heated by hot spring water.  [By Katsuki Umeda 2007.  Development and 
sustainability of vegetable farming in geothermal greenhouses. 
``Geographical Review of Japan''  http://doi.org/10.4157/grj.80.225]
	[See Biratori Town in Hidaka sub-prefecture for tomato 
production.]
	As for sightseeing, Mori Station is the birth place of Ika-
meshi (squid rice).  Squid rice became famous all over the country for 
department stores' station-lunch festivals.  #9

NOTE

#1  Mori Town belongs to Kayabe county (Kayabe-gun). The name 
``Kayabe'' comes from ``kaya-un-pe'' in Ainu language.  It means 
``sail, exist, place.''  It signified Mt. Komagatake.  Ainu people 
viewed the shape of the mountain as a sailing ship.
	[See Nanae Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for Mt. Komagatake.]
	The Hazard Map of Komagatake Volcano was published in 1983.  It 
was the first volcano hazard map in the country.  The map included the 
towns of Mori, Shikabe, and Nanae.  Today, each municipality publshes 
own hazard map.
	Who makes hazard maps?  The answer is consulting companies. 
They are the main employers of graduates from geological and 
geographical faculties. [By Kazutaka Mannen 2020.  ``Volcanoes as seen 
from cutting-edge science'' Bestbook (written in Japanese).]  Many of 
my classmates work for consulting companies.

#2  The pronunciation of ``Mori Town'' in Japanese is ``Mori-machi.'' 
Other towns in Hokkaidou are pronounced ``-chou,'' for example, 
Kayabe-chou and Yakumo-chou.
	The municipality decides the pronunciation.  It is said that 
``-machi'' is located mainly in eastern Japan and ``-chou'' is located 
mainly in western Japan.  According to the Chuu-nichi Shinbun 
(20210719), the town hall surveyed old telegrams and old gazetteers, 
and decided the name ``Mori-machi'' in 1987.
	Cf. The former Ishikari 10 towns in Ishikari City are mixture 
of ``-machi'' and ``-chou.''
	[See Ishikari City in Ishikari sub-prefecture for the former 
Ishikari 10 towns.]
	The river name ``Torizaki'' comes from ``torii (shrine gate)'' 
in Japanese.  There was a shrine in the forest.  It had many Torii 
gates.  The place was called Torii-ga-saki (shrine gate, of, cape).
	On the map published by Takeshirou Matsuura in 1859 (http://
koukita.github.io/touzaiezo/map/), the river is written as Torisaki-
kawa.
	[See Setana Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for Japanese river 
names.]
  
#3  The first immigrants came to Sawara (now Mori Town) from Kanita 
in 1532.  Kanita was located what is now Sotogahama Town in Aomori 
Prefecture) in 1532.  [By ``Sawara-chou-shi (Sawara Town history)'' 
published in 2000.]
	The former Sawara Town has a long history of Japanese 
immigrants, therefore, the origin of the name is unclear.  These are 
estimations from the book ``Sawara-chou-shi'';
	(1) The name (Sawara) comes from ``sar'' in Ainu language.  It 
means ``reed.''  (2) The name comes from ``sarki'' in Ainu language.  
It also means ``reed.''  (3) The name comes from ``sawara (suna-
hara)'' in Japanese.  It means ``sandy, field.''

#4  In the beginning of the Meiji period, the former Tokugawa Shogunate 
forces landed on the coast of Washinoki.  It was the beggining of the 
Hakodate War.  (The Hakodate War was the final phase of the Boshin 
War.)
	The commanding officers of the Tokugawa Shogunate were Takeaki 
Enomoto and Toshizou Hijikata.  They were aboard the battleships Kaiyou 
and Kaiten.  Kaiyou was made in the Netherlands.  Kaiten was made in 
Prussia (now Germany).
 	The landing took place on December 4th, 1868.  A strong wind 
was blowing on the day.  The local wind is called Taba-kaze.
	(The battleship Kaiyou was sunk in Esashi.  The battleship 
Kaiten was sunk in Hakodate.  See Easahi Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture 
for the local wind Taba-kaze.)
	[See Esashi Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for the battleship 
Kaiyou.  See Hakodate City in Oshima sub-prefecture for the Boshin 
War.]

#5  National Route 5 runs along a railway.  The national highway 
connects Hakodate and Sapporo.  The road opened in 1873 (Meiji 6).  At 
the time, the road was called Sapporo-hondou (Sapporo Main Road).  It 
crossed Uchiura Bay (Volcano Bay) from Mori to Muroran by ferry.
	In 1878 (Meiji 11), a British writer, Isabella Lucy Bird, 
stayed at an inn in Mori.  She was traveling from Hakodate to Biratori 
to see Ainu culture.  She documented Mori like this, ``Mori is a large 
village in the south of Volcano Bay, however, the houses are about to 
collapse at any moment.''  But she liked the view from the inn.
	[See Nanae Town in Oshima sub-prefecture, Toyoura Town in Iburi 
sub-prefecture, and Biratori Town in Hidaka sub-prefecture for the 
British writer.]

#6  The Sawara branch route of the Hakodate Main Line connects Mori 
Station and Oonuma Station.  It passes through the former Shikabe Town. 
During the Second World War, the branch route was constructed to 
increase transportation capacity.
	It was constructed using two existing railroads; Oshima-
kaigan-tetsudou (Oshima Coastal Railway) and Oonuma-dentetsu (Oonuma 
Electric Railway).  In June 1945, the branch route opened.  In August 
1945, Japan surrendered to the war.

#7  As for animal husbandry in Mori, there are swine farms managed by 
NH Foods (Nippon Ham Foods).  The company's processing plant is located 
in neighboring Yakumo Town.  As for food processing, Nichirei Foods 
produces croquettes and minced cutlets.  Maruha Nichiro produces salmon 
flakes and minced chicken.
	In the garden of Nichirei Foods, there is a monument that 
commemorates the birth place of frozen food in Japan.  The frozen food 
business started in 1920 (Taishou 9).
	At the time, Kuzuhara-shoukai (now Nichirei Foods) produced 
frozen fish using a charcoal gas engine.  The frozen fish was sold in 
Tokyo.  The company's freezing plant was constructed by American 
father-and-son engineers. The company owned reefer ships.
	* * *
	Regarding frozen food, the first home refrigerator was sold by 
GE (General Electric) in the USA in the 1920s.  After the 1960s, 
Japanese companies produced a lot of refrigerators.
	My parents used a Hitachi refrigerator for 50 years.  The next 
refrigerator was broken in two years.  Nowadays, companies pursue 
profit.  Never broken refrigerators are bad for them.

#8  As for power generation in Mori Town, Hokkaidou Electric Power 
(Hokuden) runs a geothermal power plant. It is located on the slope 
of Nigorikawa caldera.  Geothermal power generation is suitable to the 
volcanic country.  There is no fuel cost.
	However, geothermal power generation has these disadvantages; 
(1) The output is small compared to the size of the building.  (2) 
Construction costs are high.  (3) Many volcanoes are located in 
national parks, therefore, nature conservation laws restrict the 
construction. 

#9  Abe-shouten (Abe Store) started to sell Ika-meshi (squid rice) at 
Mori Station in 1941.  It was during the Second World War.  All trains 
stopped at Mori Station, because the location was the junction of the 
Hakodate Main Line and the Oshima Coastal Railway (Oshima-kaigan-
tetsudou).
	Squid rice became popular among young soldiers who stationed in 
Hokkaidou.  At the time, the catch of flying squid was good.  Also, 
squid rice can be cooked with a small amount of rice.  During the war, 
rice distribution was controlled.
	Nowadays, many companies sell squid rice.  The original Abe-
shouten's squid rice was not sold at sourvenir shops, because the 
expiry date was one day.  It was sold through demonstration sales at 
department stores. 
	The original Abe-shouten's squid rice became vacuum packed in 
2016.  Souvenir shops at Sapporo Station and New Chitose Airport 
started selling the original squid rice.  Incidentally, squid-shaped 
potteries of 4000-year-old were excavated in Mori Town in 2002.
	* * *
	As for department stores, there used to be department stores in 
front of major stations.  Nowadays, large shopping malls stand in the 
former paddy fields.  Your grandmother will remember shopping at 
department stores.  Department stores also conducted out-of-store sales 
(``gaishou''). 
