LOCATION

Yakumo [ya-ku-mo] [\u516B\u96F2] is a town in Oshima sub-prefecture, 
south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').  The area crosses the narrow part of the 
Oshima Peninsula.  It faces Uchiura Bay (Funka-wan) and the Sea of 
Japan.  The name ``Funka-wan'' is a translation of ``Volcano Bay'' into 
Japanese. 
	[See Oshima sub-prefecture for Volcano Bay.]
 	The area was newly formed by the merger of Yakumo Town and 
Kumaishi Town in 2005.  The former Yakumo Town was located along 
Uchiura Bay on the Pacific Ocean side.  The former Kumaishi Town was 
located along the Sea of Japan.

NAME

The name ``Yakumo'' is Japanese, which means ``overlapping clouds.''  
It was named by Yoshikatsu Tokugawa, who was the founder of Tokugawa 
Farm.  He quoted the name from the oldest poem.  (Tokugawa Farm was the 
birthplace of Hokkaidou's famous souvenirs; butter candy and carved 
wooden bear [a bear eating a salmon].)  #1
	The name ``Kumaishi'' comes from ``kuma-us-i'' in Ainu 
language.  It means ``fish drying site, many, place.''  The Kanji 
characters for Kumaishi [\u718A\u77F3] mean ``bear, stone.''
	With the merger of two towns (Yakumo and Kumaishi) in 2005, 
Futami county was newly established.  The name ``Futa-mi'' is Japanese, 
which means ``two seas.''
 
HISTORY

In the early Edo era, the Matsumae Domain built a guardhouse (``ban-
sho'') in Kumaishi on the Sea of Japan side.  It was the northern end 
of Japanese territory.  
	On the Pacific Ocean side, there were trading places 
(``basho'').  They were located in Nodaoi [\u91CE\u7530\u8FFD] and 
Yuurappu [\u904A\u697D\u90E8].
 	In the mid Edo era, the Matsumae Domain built a fort in 
Yamukushinai (later called as Yamakoshinai [\u5C71\u8D8A\u5185]).  It 
became the northern end of Japanese territory on the Pacific Ocean 
side.
	Then, the trading place of Yuurappu was renamed Yamakoshinai.
The main village was moved from Nodaoi to Otoshibe [\u843D\u90E8] due 
to an increase in fishing immigrants.  (On the Hakodate Main Line, 
there are Otoshibe Station, Nodaoi Station, and Yamakoshi Station [the 
former Yamakoshinai Station]).
	The following is the history of Yakumo Town after the Meiji 
period;

OLD YAKUMO TOWN; In 1872 (Meiji 5), Yamakoshinai branch of the 
Hokkaidou Development Commission (Kaitaku-shi) was established.  In 
1878 (Meiji 11), Tokugawa Farm opened.  In 1879 (Meiji 12), 
administrative offices (``kochou-yakuba'') were established in 
Yamakoshinai and Otoshibe villages. 
	In 1890 (Meiji 23), the administrative office of Yamakoshinai 
village was moved to Yakumo village.  In 1902 (Meiji 35), Yakumo 
Village (2nd-class municipality) was established. 
	[See the note of Matsumae Town for 1st-class and 2nd-class 
municipalities.]
	In 1903 (Meiji 22), Yamakoshinai Station and Yakumo Station on 
the Hokkaidou Railway (now the Hakodate Main Line) opened.  In 1907 
(Meiji 40), Yakumo Village (1st-class municipality) was established.  
In 1915 (Taishou 4), Otoshibe Village (2nd-class municipality) was 
established.  
	In 1919 (Taishou 8), Yakumo Town was established.  In 1957 
(Shouwa 32), Yakumo Town merged Otoshibe Village.

OLD KUMAISHI TOWN; In 1973 (Meiji 6), administrative offices (``kochou-
yakuba'') were established in villages of Kumaishi, Ainumanai [\u76F8
\u6CBC\u5185], and Tomarikawa [\u6CCA\u5DDD]. Those were a continuation 
of village chiefs system from the Edo era.
	In 1902 (Meiji 35), the three villages were merged and Kumaishi 
Village (2nd-class municipalities) was established.  In 1962 (Shouwa 
37), Kumaishi Town was established.  Herring fishing flourished in 
Kumaishi from the Edo era to the Meiji period.  The peak of Kumaishi's 
population was 10,049 in 1962 (Shouwa 37).  

TOWN HALL, TRAFFIC

The town hall of Yakumo is located near the mouth of the Yuurappu 
River.  It was the former Yakumo Town's town hall.  National Route 277 
(Unseki-kokudou) branches off from National Route 5 (Oonuma-kokudou) 
near the town hall.  The Hakodate Main Line runs along Uchiura Bay.  #2

INDUSTRY

Distinctive industries in Yakumo are animal husbandry, agriculture, 
fishery, and meat processing.  STATISTICS OF AGRICULTURE = pasture 
4,360 hectares in 2015, fodder 989, paddy rice 338, potatoes 90 
(including seed potatoes), adzuki beans 67, soybeans 51, green onions 
20 (mainly Nanpaku-negui), flowers 3, spinach 1, tomatoes 1, 
	(continued) --> other vegetables 95+X (pumpkins, sweet corn), 
and other grains 11; dairy cows 9,111 head in 2015, beef cattle 4,893, 
and hens 1,800.  STATISTICS OF FISHERIES = right-eye flounder 642 tons 
in 2017, salmon 403, squid (flying squid 248, other squid 1), Konbu 
kelp 178, walleye pollock 156, shellfish 144, shrimp/prawns 81, 
	(continued) --> octopus 66, yellowtail 52, crabs (snow crabs 
22, other crabs 16), herring 21, olive flounder 20, Pacific cod 19, sea 
urchins 18, mackerel 16, akta mackerel 15, sharks 9, sea trout 7, 
Hatahata 3, other fish 236, and other marine animals 118.  #3  #4
	As for meat processing, Japan Food Packer's Dounan Factory 
processes pork and beef.  The company is part of the Nippon Ham Group.
There was a Kentucky Fried Chicken's experiment farm.  It is now a 
tourist farm.  #5  #6
	As for sightseeing, Yakumo Hot Spring and Ken-ichi Hot Spring 
are located along National Route 277.  Guinkon-yu Hot Spring is located 
along the Otoshibe River.  The name ``Guinkon'' means silver-wedding-
anniversary in Japanese.
	In the former Kumaishi Town, Abalone Festival is held in late 
May.  I passed the festival during a bus excursion.  There were many 
cars.  The police guided them.

NOTE
 
#1  Yoshikatsu Tokugawa asked land granting for the former samurais in 
the Owari Domain (now Aichi Prefecture).  It was approved in 1879 
(Meiji 11) and Tokugawa Farm was established in Yuurappu district in 
Yamakoshinai village.  The area was 496 hectares.
	(The name ``Yuurappu'' comes from ``yu-rap'' in Ainu language.  
It means ``hot spring, down.'')
	In 1881 (Meiji 14), Yuurappu district was separated from 
Yamakoshinai village to be a village.  At the time, Yoshikatsu Tokugawa 
named the new village Yakumo.  It was named after the oldest poem in 
the country.  The lyrics are as follows;
``Yakumo-tatsu izumo-yaegaki tsumagomi-ni yaegaki-tsukuru 
  sono-yaegaki-wo.''
  (Overlapping clouds stand, fences within fences in Izumo, to live 
   with my wife, make fences within fences, the fences within fences).
	It is said that the poem was read by Susanoo-no-mikoto, who was 
a god of mythology.  The lyrics are mysterious.  Actually, it is an old 
song for weddings.
	Tokugawa Farm started Western-style agriculture including dairy 
farming.  In winter, farmers in Tokugawa Farm sculpted wooden bears. 
The carved bears became a famous souvenir from Hokkaidou.  The 
prototype is a carved wooden bear that Yoshichika Tokugawa brougt back 
from Switzerland as a souvenier.
	In 1927 (Shouwa 2), Tokugawa Farm owned 5,083 hectares of land,
including forests.  Tokugawa Farm was demolished after World War II.  
The Allied Powers (US Army) ordered land reform throughout the country. 
	[See Niki Town in Shiribeshi sub-prefecture for large farms 
during the Meiji period.]
	* * *
	Troubles over the land reform continue.  A family in a rural 
area owns 2-tan (20 ares) of paddy fields, although they do not 
cultivate.  They lend the land.
	The family was informed just before the enactment of the Land 
Reform Act, and borrowed the land.  After the enactment, the owner of 
the land had to transfer the land to the tenant farmer.  The land owner 
says, ``I hate them so much.  I want to kill them.'' 
 
#2  National Route 277 crosses Unseki Pass and reaches Kumaishi.  The 
pass divides Pacific Ocean side and the Sea of Japan side.  The name 
``Un-seki'' means ``cloud, stone'' in Japanese.  It signifies 
``un (kumo)'' in Yakumo and ``seki (ishi)'' in Kumaishi.
	The town hall of the former Kumaishi Town was located in the 
Sea of Japan side.  National Route 229 (Hiyama-kokudou) passes along 
the coast.  It takes about an hour by car to reach the current town 
hall.  There were many reasons for the merger across sub-prefectures.  

#3  During the Taishou period (1912-1926), farmers in Yakumo cultivated 
mainly potatoes.  The potatoes were processed into potato starch, which 
was for export to abroad.  The export of potato starch declined due to 
the Great Depression.  Dairy farming increased after the 1930s. 
	Nowadays, Yakumo is the main dairy farming region in south 
Hokkaidou.  The main breed of dairy cow is Holstein.  It is the largest 
breed among cows and cattle.  (Cows are for milk and cattle are for 
beef.) 
	Holstain has black and wihte skin.  Holstain was called 
``roppaku-gyuu'' in Japanese.  It means ``six, white, cow.''  There are 
six white spots around its nose.
	[See Eniwa City in Ishikari sub-prefecture for dairy cow.]

#4  As for fishery in Yakumo, the main catches in Pacific Ocean side 
are farmed scallops, salmon, right-eye flounder, and farmed Konbu kelp. 
	The main catches in the Sea of Japan side are walleye pollock, 
squid, and farmed abalone.  Deep sea water is used for the abalone 
culture.  Deep sea water is rich in minerals and low in bacteria. 
	Abalone is called ``awabi'' in Japanese.  It is expensive.  The 
shell is hard.  Inside the shell there is mother-of-peal (``shinju-
sou'').  The shell has holes.  The holes are used for breathing.  They 
are not eyes, although scallops have eyes.

#5  As for chicken, I think chicken tastes better in Hokkaidou. 
Chickens can grow healthy under a cool climate, without sweating.
	In Hokkaidou, fried chicken is called ``zangui.''  The word 
would have come from Chinese.  In Japanese, fried chicken is generally 
called ``kara-ague.''  It means ``Tang (old China), deep fried.''

#6  A meat processing factory is located in Yakumo Town.  Swine farms 
are located in mountainous areas in Mori Town and Imakane Towns.  In 
the past, Brazilians worked at the meat processing factory.  There was 
a Brazilian restaurant in the center of Yakumo Town.
	Masao Kanamori who instructed brass band at a local high school 
said; ``I sometimes went to the Brazilian restaurant.  Then, I was 
hooked on bossa nova.''
	Students who played musical instruments at University of 
Tsukuba also recommended ``Aguas de marco [\u00C1guas de mar\u00E7o] 
[agua-su-de-maru-so].''  It is a bossa nova song from Rio de Janeiro. 
The title means ``Waters of March.''  (The name ``Rio de Janeiro'' 
means ``River, of, January.'')
