LOCATION

Oshamanbe [o-sha-ma-n-be] [\u9577\u4E07\u90E8] is a town in Oshima 
sub-prefecture, south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').  (The official spelling 
is ``Oshamambe.'')  It is located in the root of the Oshima Peninsula. 
The area faces Uchiura Bay.  The rivers of Oshamanbe, Monbetsu, and 
Kun-nui flow.  #1  #2  #3

NAME 

The name ``Oshamanbe'' is derived from ``o-samam-pet'' in Ainu 
language, which means ``river mouth, bend, river.''  Or, it is derived 
from ``o-samampe'' in Ainu language, which means ``river mouth, 
flatfish.'' 

HISTORY

During the Edo era, in 1669, the Ainu forces from Hidaka to Matsumae.  
It was the revolt of Shakushain (Shakushain-no-tatakai).  The leader of 
the Ainu forces was Shakushain.  The Ainu forces were defeated by the 
gun corps of the Matsumae Domain along the Kun-nui River. #4 
	In 1773, the Matsumae Domain built a guardhouse (``ban-sho'') 
and Inari Shrine.  (Incidentally, in 2022, water gushed out from the 
Inari Shrine's grounds up to a height of 30 meters.)
	In 1864, the trading place (``basho'') of Yamakoshinai was 
abolished, and Yamakoshinai village and Oshamanbe village were 
established.  Yamakoshinai was located in what is now Yakumo Town.
	After the Meiji period, in 1872 (Meiji 5), Oshamanbe branch of 
Hakkaidou Development Commission was established.  In 1873 (Meiji 6), a 
village chief (``kochou'') was appointed.  It was a continuation of 
village chief system from the Edo era.  In 1903 (Meiji 36), Oshamanbe 
Station on the Hokkaidou Railway opened (now the Hakodate Main Line).  
	In 1906 (Meiji 39), Oshamanbe Village (2nd-class municipality) 
was established.  In 1923 (Taishou 12), Oshamanbe Village (1st-class 
municipality) was established.  The Nagawa Line opened (now the Muroran 
Main Line).  Oshamanbe Station became a junction.  In 1943 (Shouwa 18), 
Oshamanbe Town was established.
	[See the note of Matsumae Town for 1st-class and 2nd-class 
municipalities.]

TOWN HALL, TRAFFIC

The town hall of Oshamanbe is located near the mouth of the Oshamanbe 
River.  National Route 37 (Shizukari-kokudou) branches off from 
National Route 5 (Oonuma-kokudou [south] or Youtei-kokudou [north]).  
The Muroran Main Line branches off from the Hakodate Main Line.
	The eastern part of the area is Shizukari Pass and Rebungue 
Pass.  They are steep sea cliffs.  The first road and railroad that 
connected Hakodate and Sapporo headed inland from Oshamanbe.  Those 
road and railroad are now National Route 5 and the Hakodate Main Line. 
#5  #6

INDUSTRY

Distinctive industries in Oshamanbe are fishery and dairy farming.  
STATISTICS OF AGRICULTURE = pasture 1,412 hectares in 2015 and fodder 
239; dairy cows 2,224 head in 2015.  STATISTICS OF FISHERIES = salmon 
386 tons in 2017, shellfish 107 (mainly farmed scallop), 
	(continued) --> right-eye flounder 93, yellowtail 27, sea 
urchins 20, walleye pollock 17, crabs 10 (including horsehair crabs), 
olive flounder 13, flying squid 8, tuna 2, mackerel 1, octopus 1, 
seaweed 1, herring - (zero), other fish 38, and other marine 
animals 17.
	Fishing ports are located in Shizukari, Oshamanbe, Oonaka, and 
Kun-nui districts.  Crabs are the specialty of the town.  The lunch box 
of Oshamanbe Station is Kani-meshi (crab rice).  #7  

NOTE

#1  Oshima Peninsula is located in the south of Hokkaidou.  It can be 
defined as this; 
	``Oshima Peninsula is part of Hokkaidou island, located south 
of a line that connects Oshamanbe, Kuromatsunai Basin, and Suttsu 
Bay.''
	* * *
	As for Oshamanbe River, Natural gas is extracted in the lower 
reaches of the river.  Futamata Radium Hot Spring is located in the 
upper reaches of the river.  It is a secluded hot spring.
	As for the Kunnui River, the name comes from ``kunne-nay'' in 
Ainu language.  It means ``black, river.''  The river was black because 
it contained iron sand.  In the past, the iron sand collected in 
Oshamanbe and Yakumo was transported to steel mills in Muroran.
	[See Kyougoku Town in Shiribeshi sub-prefecture for iron 
mining.]

#2  In Ainu language, rivers are called ``nay'' or ''pet.''  The word 
``nay'' means a stream, whose course is changeable, for example, 
Wakkanai, Utashinai, and Kikonai.
	 The word ``pet'' means a river, whose course is stable.  The 
word ``pet'' is called ``betsu'' in place names, for example, Ebetsu, 
Makubetsu, and Shibetsu.  Rivers are the source of culture.
	* * *
	Typical river names in Japanese in Hokkaidou are ``Futamata-
gawa'' (54 rivers) and ``Futamata-zawa'' (42 rivers, counted by 
Geospatial Information Authority Map in March 2025.)
	The name ``Futamata-gawa'' means ``bifurcation [bi'furu-cation] 
river.''  The name ``Futamata-zawa'' means ``bifurcation stream.'' 
Things were simple in the past.

#3  These are rivers that have funny names in Oshamanbe; (1) The 
Kyuushi-battari River, which sounds like ``sudden death river'' in 
Japanese.  (2) The Warui River, which means ``bad river'' in Japanese. 
It was bad because salmons did not appear in autumn and timbers could 
not be transported.  [By Housei Nagata 1891.  ``Hokkaidou-ezo-go-
chimei-kai (Explanation of Ezo language in Hokkaidou).'']
	Cf. The name ``Enbetsu'' in Rumoi sub-prefecture has the same 
meaning.  It comes from ``wen-pet'' in Ainu language.  It means ``bad, 
river.''  It was bad because there were few salmon.  Dried salmon was 
an important food for Ainu people during the long winter.
	* * *
	These are rivers in Hokkaidou that have funny names;
	(1) The Yarikirenai River in Yuni Town, Sorachi sub-prefecture, 
which sounds ``I cannot stand it anymore! -river'' in Japanese.  The 
name comes from ``yanke-nai'' in Ainu language.  It means ``no fish, 
stream.''
	(2) The Obake River in Urakawa Town, Hidaka sub-prefecture.  It 
means ``ghost river'' in Japanese.  Ghosts appeared along the river in 
winter.  (Usually, ghosts appear in summer in Japan.  See Urakawa 
Town.)
	(3) The Osaru River in Date City, Iburi sub-prefecture.  It 
sounds like ``a little monkey river'' in Japanese.  The name comes from 
``o-sar-pet'' in Ainu language.  It means ``river mouth, reed (`ashi'), 
river.''  Ainu people make their houses using reeds.  In the upstream 
of the Osaru River, there even is Niagara Falls.  (See Date City).
	(4) The Chiri-chiri River in Shiriuchi Town, Oshima sub-
prefecture.  It sounds ``geography, geography river'' or ``dust, dust 
river'' in Japanese.  The name comes from ``chir-chir-nay'' in Ainu 
language.  It means ``bird, bird, stream.''
	(5) The Doudoromappu River in Tsubetsu Town, Okhotsk sub-
prefecture.  It sounds like ``a muddy map river'' in Japanese.  The 
name comes from ``tu-utur-oma-p'' in Ainu language.  It means ``two, 
together, enter, river.''
	(6) The Ponkikin River in Tsubetsu Town, Okhotsk sub-
prefecture.  In Google search, ``do you mean Ponkikki?,'' which was an 
old TV show.  The name comes from ``pon-kikin'' in Ainu language.  It 
means ``small, hackberry (`ezo-no-uwamizu-zakura').''
	(7) The Kemichap River in Tsubetsu Town, Okhotsk sub-
prefecture.  It sounds like ``ketchap river.''  The name comes from 
``kene-cha-p'' in Ainu language.  It means ``alder (`hano-ki'), to 
cut, river.'' Nature is affluent in Ainu culture.
 	(8) The Bochi-no-sawa River in Oketo Town, Okhotsk sub-
prefecture.  It is a Japanese name that means ``the stream of 
cemetery.''  When I read the name, I remembered ``Boot Hill 
(cemetery)'' in the pioneering years of the USA.
	(9) Gakkari-zawa in Otaru City, Shiribeshi sub-prefecture.  It 
is a Japanese name that means ``disappointment stream.''  It was an 
old place name around Asarigawa Hot Spring.  There were hopes and 
disappointments during the pioneering years.

#4  Shakushain was a chief of Ainu people.  Before the revolt of 
Shakushain, there were conflicts between Ainu chiefs.  A rumor spread 
among Ainu people, ``an Ainu messenger who attempted to borrow weapons 
from the Matsumae Domain was poisoned to death.''
	Then, Ainu chiefs united and revolted in many places.  The Ainu 
forces attacked trading ships, gold dust gatereres, and falcon 
catchers.  They were defeated by the gun corps of the Matsumae Domain.
	Reading the history, I thought, ``People unite when they have 
a common enemy.  They could not beat Western culture (guns).''
	It is also said that the background to the revolt was the trade 
imbalance between Ainu people and Japanese people.  Also, the eruption 
of Mt. Tarumae in 1667 may have caused food shortages.
 
