LOCATION

Kaminokuni [ka-mi-no-ku-ni] [\u4E0A\u30CE\u56FD] is a town in Hiyama 
sub-prefecture, south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').  The area faces the Sea 
of Japan.  Forests occupy 92 percent of the area.  The Amanogawa River 
flows from Mt. Tongari.  The Ishizaki River flows from Mt. 
Dai-sen-guen.

NAME

The name ``Kami-no-kuni'' is Japanese.  It means ``upper, of, 
country.''  In the 15th century, the Andou clan in Tsugaru (now Aomori 
Prefecture) entered Ezo (now Hokkaidou Prefecture).  They called the 
western part ``Kami-no-kuni'' and the eastern part ``Shimo-no-kuni.''  
The name ``Shimo-no-kuni'' means ``country, of, lower.''
	Kami-no-kuni was near to the Andou clan's homeland.  Shimo-no-
kuni was located in what is now Hokuto and Hakodate cities.  The Andou 
clan also governed Kami-no-kuni and Shimo-no-kuni in their home land 
(now Aomori and Akita prefectures).

HISTORY

In the early 13th century, the Andou clan traded with Ainu people.  
They also managed exiles from the Kamakura Shogunate.  In the mid 15th 
century, the Nanbu clan advanced to Tsugaru, and Masasue Andou and his 
vassals escaped to Ezo.  #1
 	Masasue Andou built 12 forts in Ezo.  In the area what is now 
Kaminokuni, there were two forts; Hanazawa-date and Hiishi-date. 
Japanese settlements were built around the forts.  Those were ones of 
the oldest Japanese settlements in Ezo.  #2  #3
	[See Hakodate City and Nanae Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for 
the Andou clan.  See Fukushima Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for the 
oldest Japanese village.]
	Koshamain's War occurred in 1457.  Koshamain was an Ainu chief. 
Nobuhiro Takeda, who was a vassal of the Andou clan, ended the war.  In 
the 16th century, the main fort in Ezo moved from Kaminokuni to 
Matsumae. 
	During the Edo era (from 17th to 19th century), Kaminokuni was 
governed by the Matsumae Domain.  Kaminokuni was a village of temples, 
shrines, and fishing.
	After the Meiji period, in 1872 (Meiji 5), administrative 
offices (``kochou-yakuba'') were established in Kaminokuni and Shiofuki 
[\u6C50\u5439] villages.  Those were a continuation of village chief 
system from the Edo era.
	In 1879 (Meiji 12), three administrative offices for seven 
villages were established; One was for the villages of (1) Kaminokuni, 
(2) Kita [\u5317], and (3) Oodome [\u5927\u7559]; 
	(continued) --> One was for the villages of (4) Shiofuki and 
(5) Kinoko [\u6728\u30CE\u5B50]; One was for the villages of (6) 
Ishizaki [\u77F3\u5D0E] and (7) Chiisago [\u5C0F\u7802\u5B50].
	In 1902 (Meiji 35), Kaminokuni Village (2nd-class municipality) 
was established by the merger of seven villages.  In 1967 (Shouwa 42), 
Kaminokuni Town was established.
	[See the note of Matsumae Town for 2nd-class municipality.]

TOWN HALL, TRAFFIC

The town hall of Kaminokuni is located near the mouth of the Amanogawa 
River.  National Route 228 (Matsumae-kokudou) runs along the sea.  #4  
#5
	Previously, the Esashi Line ran along the valley of the 
Amanogawa River.  It connected Esashi Station and Kikonai Station until 
2014.  The former station sites remain (when I'm writing this draft in 
2019).  There was also Amanogawa Station for sightseeing.  The name 
``Amanogawa'' means the Milky Way in Japanese.

INDUSTRY

Distinctive industries in Kaminokuni are fishing, paddy rice 
cultivation, and forestry.  STATISTICS OF AGRICULTURE = paddy rice 239 
hectares in 2015, beans (soybeans 74, adzuki beans 8, other beans 1), 
wheat 71, buckwheat 37, pasture 5, orchards 5, 
