other squid 15), octopus 25, shrimp/prawns 8, Pacific cod 7, 
	(continued) --> shellfish (abalone 1, other shellfish 6), 
yellowtail 6, tuna 6, right-eye flounder 5, sharks 4, mackerel 4, 
sardines 3, sea trout 1, herring 0, other fish 23, other marine animals 
5.  #6  #7
	As for sightseeing, Joukokuji Temple is the oldest building in 
Hokkaidou.  The current building was built in 1758.  Fort Hanazawa was 
located on a hill near the center of the town.  Nowadays, windmills 
stand on the hill.  #8  #9

NOTE

#1  As for exiles in the early 13th century, thieves and pirates were 
caught in the western country . They were taken to the eastern country 
(now Kantou region).  After their trial, some of them were exiled to 
Ezo (now Hokkaidou region).
	As for the explorers of Hokkaidou, Tadataka Inou and Takeshirou 
Matsuura are foumous.  Tadataka Inou explored in 1800 to confirm the  
coastline on the map.  Takeshirou Matsuura explored in 1845, 1846, 
1849, 1856, 1857, and 1858.  He made atlas and gazetteers of Hokkaidou.
	More than five centuries before them, Japanese people lived in 
what is now south Hokkaidou.

#2  As for Koshamain's war, in 1456, an Ainu man asked a Japanese 
blacksmith to make a large knife.  The knife is called ``makiri'' in 
Japanese.
	When the knife was made, the Ainu man quarreled over the 
quality and the price. The blacksmith got angry and stabbed the Ainu 
man to death with the knife.
	Then, Ainu people united under the chief Koshamain and attacked 
Japanese people in 1457.  The Ainu forces destroyed 10 of 12 forts. 
(``Fort'' was called ``date'' in Japanese, for example, Hakodate.)
	This is a list of the 10 destroyed forts; Shinori-date (in 
what is now Hakodate City), Usukeshi-date (Hakodate City), Nakano-date 
(Kikonai Town), Wakimoto-date (Shiriuchi Town), 
	(continued) --> Onnai-date (Fukushima Town), Oyobe-date 
(Matsumae Town), Oodate (Matsumae Town), Nebota-date (Matsumae Town), 
Haraguchi-date (Matsumae Town), and Hiishi-date (Kaminokuni Town).
	Japanese people escaped to Hanazawa-date (in what is now 
Kaminokuni Town) and Mobetsu-date (Hokuto City).  In 1458, Nobuhiro 
Takeda shot Koshamain and his son to death with a bow.  The Koshamain's 
war ended.
	The conflict between Ainu people and Japanese people continued. 
Mobetsu-date was also destroyed by the Ainu forces in 1508.

#3  Masasue Andou built 12 forts in Ezo (old Hokkaidou) and returned to 
his home land.  Then, he built Hiyama Castle in what is now Noshiro 
City, Akita Prefecture.
	The Kakizaki clan and the Takeda clan were vassals of the Andou 
clan.  They stayed in Ezo.  Nobuhiro Takeda ended the Koshamain's War 
and inherited the Kakizaki clan.  He changed his family name from 
Takeda to Kakizaki. 
	Nobuhiro Kakizaki (formerly Nobuhiro Takeda) built a new fort, 
whose name was Katsuyama-date, in what is now Kaminokuni Town.  It was 
located next to Hanazawa-date, which was one the 12 forts the Andou 
clan built.
	Mitsuhiro Kakizaki was the son of Nobuhiro Kakizaki. He moved 
the main fort from Katsuyama-date to Oodate in what is now Matsumae 
Town.  His descendant, Yoshihiro Kakizaki, founded the Matsumae Domain 
in the Edo era.
	[See Matsumae Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for the Matsumae 
Domain.]

#4  The spelling of the Amanogawa River in Kaminokuni Town is same as 
the Milky Way.  In 1614, Geronimo de Angelis, who was a Jesuit 
missionary from Sicily island, was heading for Matsumae.  He landed in 
Kaminokuni due to a heavy storm.  Later, he drew a map of Ezo and 
marked his landing point ``Tcuga [T\u00E7uga].''
	The old name of Kaminokuni was Tsuga [\u5929\u6CB3].  The 
pronunciation of the Kanji characters changed to Amanogawa [\u5929
\u306E\u6CB3].  The original name ``Tsuga'' comes from ``to-ka'' in 
Ainu language.  It means ``pond, shore.''

#5  The built-up area of Kaminokuni faces the sea.  The Okushiri 
Earthquake occurred in July 1993.  At the time, the built-up area 
of Kaminokuni suffered very little damage from tidal waves, because 
Okushiri island acted as a shield between the epicenter and Kaminokuni. 
In Okushiri island, more than 200 people died.
	[See Okushiri Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for the Okushiri 
Earthquake.]

#6  The year 1993 was a crop failure due to cold weather.  At the time, 
a crop failure division was established in the town hall of Kaminokuni. 
Rice cultivation thrived in the town.  It was like rural areas in 
Honshuu island.  
	(According to 2015 Census of Agriculture and Forestry, the area 
of rice per farm is 3.9 hectares in Kaminokuni Town.  Meanwhile, it is 
10.2 hectares in Sorachi sub-prefecture.)
	* * *
	During the crop failure, I was a university student.  I ate 
Thai rice in the canteen.  The rice was urgently imported.  Japanese 
rice production is like the Just-in-time method.  Neither farmers nor 
the government produce surplus. 
	(The Just-in-time method was adopted by Toyota Motor.  It was 
adopted during the post-war period of material shortages.  Meanwhile, 
Mass-production-method was adopted by Ford Motor in the USA.  The 
company lead the world's first motorization at the beginning of the 
20th century.)
	The year 1993 was a cold summer.  (A cols summer is called 
``reika'' in Japanese).  In the year, a large cooler was installed in 
our laboratory of geography, although we did not used it.
	When I was a child, if the temperature rose by 30 degrees 
Celsius, it was a hot day.  Nowadays, the temperature in Tokyo becomes 
above 36.5 degrees Celsius every day in summer.
	The year 2025 was a rice shortage.  It was not caused by a 
cold summer.  The summer was too hot in Tokyo.  It was caused by the 
market.  It was an imbalance between supply and demand.
	International students from Asian countries were surprised by 
the rising price of rice in supermarkets.  My wife bought Bichiku-mai 
(the government reserved rice).  Then, she bought California rice 
(Calrose).  She said, ``My pride does not allow it, but...''  (She was 
born and grown in a rural area.)  
 
#7  Edible mountain plants are called ``sansai'' in Japanese.  On May 
19, 2013, I traveled from Kikonai to Kaminokuni on a bus excursion.  I 
saw several cars parked in the mountains.  People went into the 
mountains to pick edible mountain plants.
	According to a graduation thesis submitted to Faculty of 
Letters at Hokkaidou University, fern pickers used to come Kaminokuni 
Town from Niigata Prefecture every spring.  Fern (``zenmai'' in 
Japanese) and blacken ferns (``warabi'') are typical edible mountain 
plants. 
	Fern pickers stayed in mountain huts where they collected, 
boiled, and dried ferns.  When the harvest season was over, they rented 
freight trains and shipped dried ferns to Oosaka.
	According to Takeo Ichikawa's book ``Nihon-no-shiki-to-kurashi 
(Four seasons and life of Japan)'' published in 1993, edible mountain 
plants grown in snowy regions are large and of good quality.  A family 
in Murakami (Niigata Prefecture) earned over one million yen in one 
season by picking wild edible mountain plants.  

#8  These are old buildings in Kaminokuni; (1) Joukokuji Temple, which 
is a Buddhist temple built in 1443.  That was around the year when Fort 
Hanazawa was built.  The existing building was rebuild in 1758.  The 
name ``Joukoku'' is Japanese.  The meaning is the same as 
``Kaminokuni.''  
	(2) Tategami-hachiman Shrine, which was built in 1473.  That 
was around the year when Fort Katsuyama was built.  The names 
``Tategami'' and ``Hachiman'' are Japanese.  These signify gods of war. 
The existing building was rebuild in 1699.  It was moved to the foot of 
a hill in 1895, and the name was changed to Kaminokuni-hachiman Shrine.
 	(3) The Sasanami's residence, which is the former herring 
mansion (``nishin-goten'') located in the center of Kaminokuni Town.  
It was built in the early 19th century, during the Edo era.  It is the 
oldest residence in Hokkaidou (excluding temples and shrines).
	Those buildings are designated as Important Cultural 
Properties (Juuyou-bunka-zai).  As for the oldest building in Japan, it 
is Houryuuji Temple in Nara Prefecture.  It was rebuilt in the 7th 
century.
	[See Hiyama sub-prefecture for Houryuuji temple.]
	The main buildings of temples and shrines do not have water 
facilities such as kitchens.  Therefore, temples last longer than 
ordinary houses.  
	There are many temples and shrines in traditional towns. 
Kaminokuni is one of them.  Kaminokuni was the original place of the 
Matsumae Domain.
	In the past, monks in temples and priests in shrines were like 
civil servants today.  They recorded people's names and place names.  
In addition, many people were born and many people died in the past. 

#9  There are old legends in Kaminokuni Town.  Ookura herring is one of 
them.  The story has been told since the 1590s (before the Edo era);
	``In one year, people could not catch herring until the end of 
May.  The fishing season was almost over.  At the time, an elderly 
monk, Shuukai Ookura, said to the villagers, `I will pray for herring 
to come.  If you catch herring, please share them with me.  I will 
repair my temple.'
	Villagers made a promise.  The monk tied up a sacred rope, 
fasted, and prayed.  One week later, seagulls covered the sea, Shikabe 
(albatross) gathered on the shore, whales spurted water and made big 
waves.  Schools of herring appeared.
	The catch was larger than usual years.  Villagers were very 
happy.  However, a perverse man refused to give his thanks to the monk, 
saying, `It is just late this year, not your prayer.'  He got into a 
fight with the old monk and the monk died.
	Villagers prayed to the spirit of the monk.  After the 
incident, when a small number of herring washed up on the shore in 
June, villagers called them `Ookura herring'.''
	These are other legends; ``Upside-down water pine (yew),'' 
``Beheaded pine,'' and ``The path of god.''  People may have made 
legends during the long winter.
	[See Yoichi Town in Shiribeshi sub-prefecture, Esashi Town, and 
Otobe Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for herring fishing.]
