LOCATION

Esashi [e-sa-shi] [\u6C5F\u5DEE] is a town in Hiyama sub-prefecture, 
south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').  The area faces the Sea of Japan.  The 
shape of the town is like the letter ``B.''  The narrow part is the 
mouth of the Assabu River.  (Assabu Town is located in the middle and 
upper reaches of the Assabu River.)
  	As for the original vegetation, the mountains were covered with 
Hiba trees (kind of cypress).  In the Edo era, the trees were actively 
felled.  The logs were transported down the Assabu River.  The county's 
name ``Hi-yama'' is Japanese, which means ``cypress mountain.''  #1
	[See Hiyama sub-prefecture for Hiba trees.]

NAME

The name ``Esashi'' comes from ``e-sa-us-i'' in Ainu language. It means 
``head, seashore, exist, place.''  It stands for a cape.  It signified 
Kamome island in the Port of Esashi.  The etymology of Esashi is the 
same as Esashi Town in Souya sub-prefecture.  #2

HISTORY

In 1216, Ubagami-daijinguu Shrine was established.  It is one of the 
oldest shrines in Hokkaidou.  In the late 17th century, during the Edo 
era, the Matsumae Domain built a port to transport cypress.  #3  #4
	Herring fishing thrived in the Edo era.  During the season of 
herring fishing, fishermen gathered from Honshuu island to Esashi.  The 
Port of Esashi was bustling.  Esashi became one of the largest ports of 
the Matsumae Domain along with Fukuyama (Matsumae) and Hakodate.  #5
 	In 1868 (Meiji 1), during the Boshin War, the former Tokugawa 
Shogunate forces occupied Esashi.  In 1869 (Meiji 2), the Meiji 
government forces recaptured Esashi.  They advanced to Hakodate and 
defeated the former Tokugawa Shogunate forces.
	In 1872 (Meiji 5), Esashi branch of Hokkaidou Development 
Commission (Kaitaku-shi) was established.  Administrative offices 
(``kochou-yakuba'') were established for 26 towns in the built-up area 
of Esashi.  Those were a continuation of town chief system from the Edo 
era.
	In 1880 (Meiji 13), a county office (``gun-yakusho'') for 
Hiyama and Nishi [\u723E\u5FD7] counties was established.  In 1897 
(Meiji 30), Hiyama sub-prefecture (Hiyama-shichou) was established. 
The county office of Hiyama and Nihsi was abolished.
	In 1900 (Meiji 33), Esashi Town (1st-class municipality) was 
established by the merger of 26 towns in Esashi and Gokatte [\u4E94
\u52DD \u624B] village.  In 1955 (Shouwa 30), Esashi Town merged Tomari 
[\u6CCA] Village.  The shape of Tomari Village was like the letter 
``B.'' #6  #7
	[See the note of Matsumae Town for 1st-class municipality.]

TOWN HALL, TRAFFIC

The town hall of Esashi, Hiyama sub-prefectural bureau, and the Port of 
Esashi are located to the south.  The port is the terminus of National 
Route 227 (Oono-kokudou) and National Route 228 (Matsumae-kokudou).
	A ferry line connects the Port of Esashi and Okushiri island. 
Previously, the Esashi Line connected Esashi, Kikonai, and Hakodate. 
Near the mouth of the Assabu River, National Route 229 (Hiyama-kokudou) 
branches off from National Route 227.
	 National Route 229 goes north along the coast.  National Route 
227 turns east, runs along the Assabu River, crosses the ridge, and 
leads to the Oono Plain (Hakodate Plain).  It was one of the roads by 
which the Meiji government forces advanced to Hakodate during the 
Boshin War.

