NOTE
  
#1  As for the vegetation in Esashi Town, Hiyama Ancient Forest (Hiyama-
koji-no-mori) is designated as National Natural Monument (Tennen-kinen-
butsu).  The forest is located near the border with Kaminokuni Town.  
It is far from the center of Easashi Town.
	The main trees in the protected forest are Hiba (kind of 
cypress) and Ao-todomatsu (Blue Sakhalin fir).  Hiba is also called 
Hinoki-asunaro.
	[See Hiyama sub-prefecture for Hinoki-asunaro.]
	Todomatsu (Sakhalin fir) and Ezomatsu (Yezo spruce) are typical 
conifers in central Hokkaidou (``dou-ou'').  Todomatsu has smooth bark 
and Ezomatsu has rough bark.
	Esasi-sou (Esashi grass) is a kind of white mullein [ma'lein].  
The plant was imported from Europe in the Meiji period.  It naturalized 
in Esashi Town after World War II.

#2  As for the name ``Esashi,'' there is another interpretation.  The 
name comes from ``e-sas-us'' in Ainu language.  It means ``eat, Konbu 
kelp, exist.''  There is a legend like this; ``Long ago, there was a 
famine [fe'-min].  Ainu people in the north coast came here.  They 
could survive by eating Konbu kelp.''
	[See Shin-hidaka Town in Hidaka sub-prefecture for Konbu kelp.]

#3  The festival at Ubagami-daijinguu Shrine has been held since 1644. 
It is one of the oldest festivals in Hokkaidou.  A high school 
teacher in Hokkaidou said, ``If you see a festival, you will know the 
culture.  Dou-nan (south Hokkaidou) is different.''

#4  Takeshirou Matsuura was an explorer in the Edo era.  He recorded 
place names and their locations in Ezo (now Hokkaidou).  He spent a 
winter in Esashi in 1846.  It was during his 2nd survey of Ezo.  He 
earned travel expenses by carving seals (``inkan'') in Esashi.
 
#5  Esashi-oiwake is a folk song from Esashi.  It was a song for 
herring fishing in the Edo era.  These are example lyrics;
``Kuniwo hanarete ah ezogashima yansano-ee, ikuyo nezameno namimakura''
  (I left the country [ah] and came to Ezo island [yansano-ee]. How 
   many nights did I wake up on the wave pillow?)
``Nani-wo yumemite nakukayo chidori nee, kokowa esashino karino yado''
  (What are you calling and dreaming, seagulls? [nee] This is a 
   temporary lodging in Esashi).''
``Esashi-no gogatsuwa edonimo naito, hokoru nishin-no haru-no umi.''
  (May in Esashi is nowhere even in Edo [now Tokyo], proud of the 
   spring sea with herring.)
	[See Yoichi town in Shiribeshi sub-prefecture for the song 
``Souran-bush'' that was sung during herring fishing.]
	* * * 
	In the past, herring shoals spawned off the coast of Hokkaidou 
from March to May.  Herring were processed into herring meal and 
transported to Oosaka by North-bound ship (Kitamae-bune).  Fertilizer 
wholesalers purchased herring meal.  North-bound ships departed from 
Oosaka and sailed along the Seto Inland Sea, the Sea of Japan, and 
Hokkaidou.
	In the Edo era, herring meal and dried sardines were called 
``kinpi.''  It means ``gold fertilizer'' or ``money fertilizer'' in 
Japanese.  Farmers started to buy fertilizer with money.  Previously, 
farmers used leaf litter, livestock manure, and human manure as 
fertilizers.
	``Kinpi'' was the so-called money fertilizer.  It was used for 
cultivating commercial crops such as indigo, rapeseed, and cotton. 
Those crops were mainly cultivated in western Japan.
	Herring caught in Hokkaidou was also processed into ``migaki'' 
(dried herring for eat) and transported to ``naichi (main island).''  
	[See Yoichi Town in Shiribeshi sub-prefecture, Otobe Town, and 
Kaminokuni Town in Esashi sub-prefecture for herring fishing.]
 
#6  As for the former Gokatte village, the Gokatte River and the Port 
of Gokatte are located south of the built-up area of Esashi.
	 Gokkate-ya-youkan is a souvenir from Esashi.  It is 
``youkan'' (sweet bean paste).  In the Edo era, Gokatte-gumi came from 
Nanbu (now part of Iwate and Aomori Prefectures).  Gokatte-gumi was a 
group of lumberjacks. 
	Gokkate-gumi fell Hiba trees.  They also succeeded in 
cultivating adzuki-beans in Ezo (old hokkaidou).  They made sweet 
adzuki-bean paste and presented it to the lord of the Matsumae Domain.
 
#7  As for the former Tomari Village in Esashi Town, the administrative 
office (``kochou-yakuba'') of Tomari village was built in 1878 (Meiji 
11).  [By ``2016 Esashi-chou-kyouiku-suishin-keikaku (2016 Esashi 
Town education promotion plan).'']  In 1906 (Meiji 39), Tomari Village 
(2nd-class municipality) was established.
	Before 1955, there were three Tomari villages in Hokkaidou. (1) 
Tomari Village in Hiyama county, Hiyama sub-prefecture.  It was merged 
to Esashi Town in 1955.  (2) Tomari Village in Furuu county.  It is 
still located in Shiribeshi sub-prefecture.  
	(continued) --> (3) Tomari Village in Kunashiri county.  It is 
located in Kunashir island.  Russians live on the island after 1945.  
It is a nominal municipality.  
	* * *
	I taught Japanese geography at Hokkaidou University.  In the 
class, a student from Russia pointed at Kunashir (Kunashiri) island on 
the map and said,  ``This map is funny.  I do not care, but Russians 
live in the island.  They feel sad if they see this map.'' 
	I replied, ``Here is a national university.  I could buy only 
this map.''  Kunashir island is a disputed island.

#8  Kamome island in Esashi is a tombolo.  The word ``tomboro'' is a 
geographic term that means a linked island.
	These are tourist sites in Kamome island; (1) Heishi Rock; It 
looks like a religious vase.  (2) Senjou-jiki; A large flat rock 
eroded by waves.  The name ``Senjou'' means 1,000 tatami mats.  (3) 
Yoshitsune-no-uma-iwa; A white rock that looks like the horse of 
Yoshitsune Minamoto. 
	(continued) --> (4) Benkei-no-ashiato; It is large two holes on 
a flat rock.  They look like footprints of Benkei Musashibou.  Benkei 
Musashibou was a monk soldier and a vassal of Yoshitsune Minamoto.  A 
hole in the rock on the coast is called ``en-kama.''
 	(continued) --> (5) Tokugawa Shogunate battery site;  The guns 
were set by the Matsumae Domain in 1852.  (6) Sand beaches; Two sand
beaches are open in summer.
	[See Biratori Town in Hidaka sub-prefecture and Otobe Town in 
Hiyama sub-prefecture for Yoshitsune legends.]

#9  Kaiyou was a battleship of the Tokugawa Shogunate.  It was made in 
the Netherlands.  During the Boshin War, the former Tokugawa Shogunate 
forces advanced from Hakodate to Matsumae, and then to Esashi.
	 The battleship Kaiyou also set sail from Hakodate to Matsumae, 
and then to Esashi.  In December 1869 (Meiji 1), after the occupation 
of Esashi, due to a strong wind, the battleship ran aground and sank.
The wind is called ``Taba-kaze (Taba wind).''  It is a local wind in 
Hiyma sub-prefecture in winter.
	Toshizou Hijikata was the commander of Tokugawa Shogunate 
forces.  He thought of the sunken ship, cried, and hit the trunk of a 
pine tree.  Later, a not appeared on the pine tree.  The not is called 
``Toshizou's fist (Toshizou-no-kobushi).''
	The pine tree is called the Pine of Lament (Nagueki-no-matsu). 
It is located in front of the old administrative office of Hiyama and 
Nishi counties.
	[See Hakodate City in Oshima sub-prefecture for the Boshin 
War.]

#10  The local wind ``Taba-kaze'' sank the battleship Kaiyou.  It blows 
from the northwest in winter.  Japanese fishermen feared the wind.  
They believed that the wind had a soul.  They called the wind Tama-kaze 
(soul wind).  The pronunciation changed to Taba-kaze.
	Houses in Esashi were surrounded by fences in winter.  The 
fences were made of tree branches.  The sound of the wind hitting the 
fences was called ``Mogari-bue (Mogari, whistle).''  (The word 
``mogari'' means a fence made of tree branches or bamboo.)  That was 
the soundscape of Esashi in winter.  
	Today, windmills stand on the mountains in Esashi.  They are 
managed by Esashi Wind Power, a subsidiary of J-Power (Electric Power 
Development Company).
	These are local winds in Hokkaidou island; (1) Taba-kaze in 
Esashi Town, Hiyama sub-prefecture, (2) Dashi-kaze in Suttsu Town, 
Shiribeshi sub-prefecture, (3) Hidaka-shimo-kaze in Samani Town, Hidaka 
sub-prefecture, 
	(continued) --> (4) Shikata in Erimo Town, Hidaka sub-
prefecture, (5) Aikaze in Ishikari City, Ishikari sub-prefecture, and 
(5) Bafun-kaze in the Tokachi Plain, Tokachi sub-prefecture and other 
places.
	In the past, due to a strong wind in early spring, 60 herring 
fishing boats sank.  A novel depicts Kuma-kaze (bear wind).  When a 
man-eating bear was killed, a strong wind blew.
	[See Haboro Town in Rumoi sub-prefecture for the shipwreck.  
See Tomamae Town in Rumoi sub-prefecture for the man-eating bear.]
        * * *
        Long ago, an elderly Ainu woman lived near the Port of Esashi. 
Her name was Orii.  She lived near the Port of Esashi.  She was a 
prophet.  She predicted weather and wind.
	Orii also mentioned the size of fishing net for herring 
fishing.  The size should be 5-shaku 3-sun (160 centimeters) in height. 
It should have 63 meshes.  It meant a small net.
	During the Edo era, people followed her words.  Herring came 
every year.  After the Meiji period, people used larger nets and the 
catch of herring decreased.  Incidentally, the average height of a man 
was about 5-shaku (152 centimeters) in the Edo era.
 
#11  As for old buildings in Esashi, the former Nakamura's residence 
has been designated as an Important Cultural Property (Juuyou-bunka-
zai).  The residence was built from the end of the Edo era to the Meiji 
period.  The owner was a merchant from Oumi (now Shiga Prefecture).
	The Nakamura's residence was a shipping wholesaler.  The 
buildings of the residence are connected by passages.  The architecture 
is called kaisen-donya-kenchiku [\u56DE\u8239\u554F\u5C4B\u5EFA\u7BC9] 
(shipping wholesaler architecture).
	In the past, along the Port of Esashi, shipping wholesalers 
such as the Nakamura's residence were lined up.  The wholesalers had 
piers on the water to transport cargo to ships.
	Oumi merchants traded on ships called Kitamae-bune (North-bound 
ships).  The hometown of Oumi merchants was what is now Higashi-oumi 
City in Shiga Prefecture.  Esashi Town and Higashi-oumi City are sister 
cities. 
 	``North-bound ship'' was also called ``Sengoku-bune.''  The 
word ``sen-goku-bune'' means ``1,000-koku, ship'' in Japanese.  One 
``koku'' equals 150 kg in case of rice.  The ship could carry 150 tons 
of rice.
	One ``koku'' of rice was about one ``ryou'' of money in the mid 
Edo era.  The sales of one voyage per North-bound ship amounted to 
1,000-ryou of money in the mid Edo era.  One ``ryou'' of money was 
equivalent to about 50,000 yen today. 
	[See Otobe Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for one ``koku'' of 
herring.  See Kuriyama Town in Sorachi sub-prefecture for one ``koku'' 
of rice wine.]
