LOCATION

Assabu [a-ssa-bu] [\u539A\u6CA2\u90E8] is a town in Hiyama sub-
prefecture, south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').  Assabu is an inland town. 
The area corresponds to the basin of the Assabu River, which flows to 
the Sea of Japan.  The area of Assaabu seems to face the sea, but the 
mouth of the Assabu River is included in Esashi Town.
	As for vegetation, Assabu is the northern limit of Hiba trees 
(Hinoki Asunaro trees), which are a kind of cypress [sa'i-pruhs].  
Assabu is also the southern limit of Todo-matsu trees, which are a 
kind of fir.
	[See Hiyama sub-prefecture for Hiba tree.]

NAME

The name ``Assabu'' is derived from ``hacam-pet'' in Ainu language.  It 
means ``starling, river.''  It signified the Assabu River.  The 
etymology is the same as Hassamu in Nishi Ward, Sapporo City, Ishikari 
sub-prefecture.  #1

HISTORY

In the Edo era, the Matsumae Domain cut cypress trees after the 1670s. 
Woodcutters from the main island (now Honshuu island) immigrated.
	In the beginning of the Meiji period, in 1868 (Meiji 1), the 
Matsumae Domain established Tate Castle.  Tate Castle was located in 
the upper reaches of the Assabu River.  The castle was used during the 
Boshin War (1868-1869).  #2  #3  
	In 1876 (Meiji 9), the administrative office (``kochou-
yakuba'') of Gamushi [\u4FC4\u866B] village was established.  It was a 
continuation of village chief (``kochou'') system from the Edo era.  #4
	In 1879 (Meiji 12), the administrative office of Gamushi 
village was re-established.  That covered four villages; Gamushi, 
Tsuchihashi [\u571F\u6A4B], Mena [\u76EE\u540D], and Akanuma [\u8D64
\u6CBC].
	In 1800 (Meiji 13), the administrative office of Gamushi 
village covered five villages; Gamushi, Tsuchihashi, Mena, Akanuma, and 
An-noro [\u5B89\u91CE\u5442].  Those five villages existed in the Edo 
era for forestry. 
	In 1801 (Meiji 14), the administrative office of Gamush village 
covered seven villages; Gamushi, Tsuchihashi, Mena, Akanuma, An-noro, 
Tate [\u9928], and Uzura [\u9D89].
	In 1906 (Meiji 39), Assabu Village (2nd-class municipality) was 
established by the merger of seven villages.  In 1963 (Shouwa 38), 
Assabu Town was established.
	[See the note of Matsumae Town for 2nd-class municipality.]

TOWN HALL, TRAFFIC

The town hall of Assabu is located near the confluence of the 
Assabu River and the An-noro River.  The town hall was built at the 
former site of Hiyama Agricultural Experiment Station.
	National Route 227 (Oono-kokudou) passes the center of Assabu 
town.  In the past, the national highway was called Uzura-sandou (Quail 
[kwayl] mountain trail).  It was one of the routes that the Meiji 
government forces advanced to Hakodate.

INDUSTRY

Distinctive industries in Assabu are agriculture and forestry. 
STATISTICS OF AGRICULTURE = beans (soybeans 484 hectares in 2015, 
adzuki beans 196, other beans 7), paddy rice 555, potatoes 489, wheat 
373, buckwheat 171, sugar beets 44, orchards 37 (grapes 21), 
	(continued) --> pasture 24, broccoli 24, cabbage 22, fodder 21, 
barley 17, green onions 7, melons 6, carrots 2, yams 1, Chinese cabbage 
1, spinach 1, flowers 1, other vegetables 346+X (including pumpkins, 
asparagus, sweet corn), and other grains 77; dairy cows - (zero) in 
2015.  #5
	May-queen potatoes are a local specialty.  May-queen is a 
popular cultivar along with Danshaku (baron).  The country sign 
(gateway sign) of Assabu is a May-queen boy (or girl) whose face is 
long and smooth.  #6
 
NOTE
  
#1  Stalings are called Muku-dori in Japanese.  Stalings in Japan are 
white-cheeked starlings (grey starlings).  The word ``muku-dori'' means 
``Muku tree, bird.''  Muku tree is a kind of deciduous broad-leaved 
tree.
	In Hokkaidou island, the bird is also called Sakura-dori, which 
means ``cherry tree, bird.''  The bird migrates from the south during 
the cherry blossom season.
	[See Matsumae Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for cherry 
blossom.]
	When I lived in Tsukuba City, Ibaraki Prefecture, a huge flock 
of starlings covered the evening sky.  I watched it from the balcony.
The sky was filled with the birds.

#2  In the past, tree felling started in early winter.  The forest 
floor was covered with snow.  The snow provides good visibility.  
Woodcutters could move smoothly in winter.  (In summer, bamboo grass 
and grass are plentiful.) 
	Cypress trees in Hokkaido island are ``Hiba.''  Cypress trees 
in Honshu island are ``Hinoki'' and ``Hiba.''
	[See Hiyama sub-prefecture for cypress tree.]
	Woodcutters hauled logs to the river on sleighs.  Melting snow 
flooded the river in spring.  Woodcutters floated the logs down the 
river in spring.
	The woodcutter in Assabu brought Shishi-odori dance (Dear 
dance) from their homeland.  The dance became an annual event at Hiyama
guardhouse.
	Guardhouses in Ezo [now Hokkaidou] were called ``ban-sho'' in 
Japanese.  They were run by the Matsumae Domain.
	* * *
	A large forest fire occurred in 1695.  Subsequently, the 
Matsumae Domain banned logging from 1770 to 1807 to prevent 
deforestation.  A large forest fire also occurred in 1876.
	Very few natural forests remain.  Today, tourists see huge 
forests in Hokkaidou and think they are natural, however, those were 
felled and burned in the past.
	In Assabu Town, a natural forest has designated as National 
Natural Monument (Tennen-kinen-butsu) since 1928.  It is ``Uzura-gawa-
goyou-matsu-jisei-hokugen-chitai (Northern Limit of White Pine Natural 
Growing Area along the Uzura River).''
	[See Esashi Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for another natural 
forest.]
	As for snowy mountains, a female member of Hokkaidou University 
Mountaineering Club said, ``When it snows, we can go into mountains 
that we could not in summer.  In summer, bamboo grass (``sasa'') and 
dwarf pine trees (``haimatsu'') block the way.  There also are 
mosquitoes and bears in summer. 
 	As for sleigh and sled, parents move their children using 
plastic sleds in Sapporo City.  People have used sleigh and sled since 
antiquity.
	[See Naie Town in Sorach sub-prefecture for sleigh.]
 
#3  Tate Castle was built inland in 1868 (Meiji 1).  The castle was 
built inland by the Matsumae Domain to avoid naval artillery.  It was 
during the Boshin War.  The previous Fukuyama Castle (Matsumae Casle) 
was located along the coast.
	For the same reason, the capital of the Choushuu Domain moved 
from Hagui to Yamaguchi.  (Yamaguchi is the capital of Yamaguchi 
Prefecture now.)  Hagui is located along the Sea of Japan and Yamaguchi 
is located inland.  The relocation of the capital was occured in 1863. 
The Edo era, which was ruled by the Tokugawa Shogunate, ended in 1867.
	* * *
	In December 1868 (Meiji 1), the former Tokugawa Shogunate 
forces advanced to Matsumae Castle.  The Matsumae Domain's forces 
escaped to Tate Castle.  It was November by the lunar calendar 
(``taiin-reki'') used at the time.  (It was December in the solar 
calendar [``taiyou-reki''] that is used now.)  
	In Tate Castle, Mikami Choujun fought using a cutting board as 
a shield.  He a monk soldier of the Matsumae Domain.  He was killed to 
allow his allies [a'laiz] to escape.  Tate Castle was captured and 
burned by the former Tokugawa Shogunate forces.
	The lord of the Matsumae Domain somehow managed to find a ship 
in Kumaishi.  He and his family set sail to the rough winter sea.  They 
headed for Hirosaki.  Then, the Matsumae Domain's forces surrendered. 
(Kumaishi district is located in Yakumo Town.)
	In May 1869 (Meiji 2, solar calendar), the Meiji government 
forces landed near the mouth of the Himekawa River.  The Meiji 
government forces advanced south and occupied Esashi.  (The Himekawa 
River is located in Otobe Town.)
	In June 1869, the Meiji government forces advanced to Hakodate 
and ended the Boshin War.  The month was May by the lunar calendar 
used at the time.
	[See Hakodate City in Oshima sub-prefecture for the Boshin 
War.]
	After the Boshin War, the Matsumae Domain was renamed the Tate 
Domain.  In August 1871 (Meiji 4, solar calendar), all domains in Japan 
were abolished.  Prefectures were established.  In Hokkaidou, Tate 
Prefecture was established in the south.  The other areas were governed 
by the Hokkaidou Development Commission (Kaitaku-shi). 
	In October 1871 (solar calendar), Aomori Prefecture merged Tate 
Prefecture.  In 1872 (Meiji 5), the Hokkaidou Development Commission 
governed the whole Hokkaidou, including the area of the former Tate 
Prefecture.
	Meiji was a turbulent period.  After a turbulent period, 
new religions expands.
	[See Hokkaidou University in Kita Ward, Sapporo City, Ishikari 
sub-prefecture, for new religion.]
  
#4  As for the name ``Gamushi,'' there is Gamushi Hot Spring along the 
tributary of the An-noro River.  The name ``Gamushi'' comes from 
``kamuy-us-i'' in Ainu language.  It means ``god, exist, place.''  The 
word ``god'' in the name means bear.  Ainu people considered bears to 
be gods.
	[See Noboribetsu City in Iburi sub-prefecture for bear.]
  
#5  Local specialties of Assabu Town are Hikari-kuro-daizu (shining 
black soybeans) and Kuro-mame-purin (black-bean pudding).
	When I conducted field survey in Hokkaidou in the 2000s, I 
heard that black soybeans are fit for machine harvesting.  The black 
color hides the stains that gets splashed onto the beans when 
mechanical harvesters cut the stems.  It was around the time that 
mechanized soybean harvesting started.  [By T. Nihei 2007.  The 
regional bases carrying the upland farming of Tokachi, Hokkaidou. 
``Jinbun-chirigaku-kenkyuu'' http://www.researchgate.net/publication/
388527604]

#6  The potato cultivar ``May-queen'' was bred in 1900 by the British 
seed company Sutton & Sons.  May-queen was named after the queen who 
was chosen at the May Day festival.
	May-queen was imported to Japan from the USA during the Taishou 
period (1912-1925).  In 1928 (Shouwa 3), Hiyama Agricultural Experiment 
Station designated May-queen and Danshaku as recommended potato 
cultivars.  Hiyama Agricultural Experiment Station was located in 
Gamushi district, Assabu Village. 
	[See Imakane Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture and Kucchan Town in 
Shiribeshi sub-prefecture for Danshaku potatoes.]
	* * *
	May-queen is a popular ingredient in Oden (winter pot dish) in 
the Kansai region.  (Kansai is located in the central part of Japan. 
It is considered as ``western Japan [nishi-nihon].'')  May-queen 
potatoes do not fall apart when they are soaked in hot soup for a long 
time.  I grew up in eastern Japan and have never seen potatoes in Oden.
	* * *
	Sapporo Shusei is a distilling company.  The head office of 
Sapporo Shusei is located in Nishi Ward, Sapporo City, Ishikari sub-
prefecture.  The main factory of Sapporo Shusei is located along the 
Assabu River.
	Sapporo Shusei in Assabu Town makes Shouchuu (liquor).  The 
liquor is distilled from potatoes and sweet potatoes, which are 
cultivated in south Hokkaidou.  Next to the distilling factory is a 
potato shipping center that is run by agricultural cooperative.
	[See Nishi Ward in Sapporo City, Ishikari sub-prefecture, for 
liquor production.]
	I did not know that sweet potatoes are cultivated in Hokkaidou 
as a commercial crop.  Sweet potatoes are cultivated under a warm 
climate.  Sweet potato seeds are weak in cold.  In my hometown (Ibaraki 
Prefecture), sweet potato seeds were preserved in a deep hole.  The 
depth was about the height of a man.  [By T. Nihei et al. 2000. 
Regional characteristics of production and distribution of sweet 
potatoes in Hitachi-naka City. ``Chiiki-chousa-houkoku'' http://
www.researchgate.net/publication/386245461]
