#1
  
LOCATION

Otobe [o-to-be] [\u4E59\u90E8] is a town in Hiyama sub-prefecture, 
south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').   Otobe is located in the west of the 
Oshima Peninsula.  The area faces the Sea of Japan.  Forests occupy 87 
percent of the area.

NAME

The name ``Otobe'' comes from ``o-to-un-pe'' in Ainu language. 
It means ``river mouth, swamp, exist, thing (river).''  It signified 
the Hime River, which flows through the center of the town.  In the Edo 
era, the river was called Otohe.  [By Takeshirou Matsuura's map 
published in 1859; http://koukita.github.io/touzaiezo/map/]  #2  

HISTORY

In the Edo era, the area was governed by the Matsumae Domain.  Herring 
fishing thrived.  According to oral tradition, Hanaiso-suwa Shrine was 
established in 1617 (Guen-na 3).  The shrine's name is recorded in a 
document written in 1704.  #3
	After the Meiji period, in 1869 (Meiji 2), the Meiji government 
forces landed at Otobe.  It was during the Boshin War.  (Boshin War was 
a civil war.)  They advanced to Esashi and then to Hakodate.  They 
defeated the former Tokugawa Shogunate forces and ended the war.  #4
 	In 1879 (Meiji 12), the administrative office (``kochou-
yakuba'') of Otobe village was established.  It covered villages of 
Komonai [\u5C0F\u8302\u5185] and Toppu [\u7A81\u7B26].  The 
administrative office of Mitsuya [\u4E09\u30C4\u8C37] village was 
established.  It covered Kabashira [\u868A\u67F1] village.
 	In 1902 (Meiji 35), Otobe Village (2nd-class municipality) was 
established by the merger of five villages.  In 1965 (Shouwa 40), Otobe 
Town was established.
	[See the note of Matsumae Town for 2nd-class municipality.]

TOWN HALL, TRAFFIC

The town hall of Otobe is located near the mouth of the Hime River.  
National Route 229 (Hiyama-kokudou) runs along the sea.  The national 
highway connects old settlements that flourished in fishery or 
forestry.  #5

INDUSTRY

Distinctive industries in Otobe are fishery, agriculture, fish 
processing, and forestry.  STATISTICS OF AGRICULTURE = paddy rice 127 
hectares in 2015, soybeans 89, broccoli 26, adzuki beans 17, fodder 9, 
pasture 4, strawberries 2, orchards 2, radishes 1,
	(continued) --> other vegetables 32+X (including lily bulbs), 
and other grains 20; dairy cows - (zero) in 2015.  STATISTICS OF 
FISHERIES = walleye pollock 286 tons in 2017, squid (flying squid 214, 
other squid 1), sea urchins 39, octopus 32, salmon 13, Pacific cod 5,
	(continued) --> olive flounder 3, Konbu kelp 3, shrimp/prawns 
2, yellowtail 1, right-eye flounder 1, atka mackerel 1, abalone 1, 
herring 0, other fish 17, and other marine animals 16 (including sea 
cucumbers).
	Fishing ports are located in Otobe, Guen-na, and Toyohama.  As 
for other industries, a factory of CAC Cosmetics and Tomioka winery are 
located.  The founder of CAC Cosmetics was born in a pharmacy in Otobe. 
	Tomioka winery was founded in 1976.  A distilling company, 
Sapporo-shusei, acquired Tomioka winery in 2008.  The head office of 
Sapporo-shusei is located in Nishi Ward, Sapporo City, Ishikari sub-
prefecture.
 	As for sightseeing, Guen-na-dai Beach Park has been selected as 
one of the 100 Beaches of Japan.  (The 100 Beaches of Japan is 
designated by the Ministry of the Environment.)  It is the only 100 
Beaches in Hokkaidou island.  The country sign (gateway sign) of Otobe 
depicts the artificial seawater pool at Guen-na-dai Beach Park.
	These are other scenic locations.  (1) Cape Shibi-no-saki, 
which is andesite columnar jointing.  The shape resembles tuna scales.  
The word ``shibi'' means tuna in old Japanese.  (The word ``andesite'' 
is ``anzan-gan'' in Japanese.  The word ``columanr jointing'' is 
``chuujou-setsuri'' in Japanese.)
	(continued) --> (2) Cape Tateno-saki, whose nickname is 
the Grand Canyon of the Orient.  (3) Takise coast, which is known for 
Shira-hura.  Shira-fura is a white coastal cliff.   #6

NOTE
 
#1  The Kanji characters for Nishi-gun (Nishi county) are difficult to 
read even for Japanese people.  In the beginning of the Meiji period, 
the name was decided. 
	Takeshirou Matsuura, who was an explorer of Ezo (now 
Hokkaidou), suggested the name ``Nishi (West)'' for the county.  He 
suggested an easy Kanji character to Nishi [\u897F].  [By Hidezou 
Yamada & Toshikazu Sasaki eds. 1988. ``Ainu-go-chimei-shiryou-syuusei 
(Ainu language place name material collection).''  Soufuu-kan ISBN 
4883230368]
	It was changed to difficult Kanji characters to Nishi [\u723E
\u5FD7], because there were identical names in Honshuu island.

#2  The name ``Otohe'' means ``river mouth, swamp, exist, thing'' in 
Ainu language.  As the name suggests, there were many swamps and ponds 
in the lower reaches of the Otohe River (now Hime River).  They were 
reclaimed and turned into paddy fields and a built-up area.
	The current river name ``Hime'' means ``princess'' or ``noble 
lady'' in Japanese.  It refers to Shizuka-gozen in the case of Otobe 
Town.   Shizuka-gozen was a ``mekake (concubine)'' of Yoshitsune 
Minamoto.
	Yoshitsune Minamoto was a commander of the Minamoto clan in 
the 12th century.  He was killed in battle in Oushuu (now Touhoku 
region), but many legends mention that he fled to Ezo (now Hokkaidou).  
This is one of the Yoshitune legends in Otobe;
	``Shizuka-gozen came Otohe in search of Yoshitune.  She could 
not find him, because he had escaped far inland.  She was disappointed 
and committed suicide by drowning in the river.''  Therefore, the river 
is called the Hime River after Shizuka-gozen.
	I guess that the legend depicts the death of a courtesan 
[kou-ti-zan] in the end of Edo era or in the Meiji Period.  Cf. 
[see-eff]. There is Oiran-buchi in Minami Ward, Sapporo City, Ishikari 
sub-prefecture.  The name ``Oiran-buchi'' means ``Oiran (courtesan), 
abyss.'' Once, a courtesan committed suicide by drowning in the river.
	[See Biratori Town in Hidaka sub-prefecture and Esashi Town in 
Hiyama sub-prefecture for Yoshitsune legend.  See Oshamanbe Town in 
Oshima sub-prefecture for river names.]
 
#3  During the Tenmei period (1781-1789) in the Edo era, Otobe was 
Sengoku-basho of herring.  The word ``sengoku-basho'' means ``a trading 
place that has 1,000-koku catches of herring.''
	The word ``koku'' is an old unit of measurement.  One ``koku'' 
was equivalent to 150 kg of dried herring, or 200 kg of fresh herring. 
	[See Esashi Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for one ``koku'' of 
rice.  See Kuriyama Town in Sorachi sub-prefecture for one ``koku'' of 
rice wine.]
 	During the Tenmei Famine [fa'min] (1782-1788) and the Tenpou 
Famine (1833-1839), Japanese people migratede from Nanbu, Hirosaki, and 
Akita to Otobe.  (Nanbu was what is now Iwate and Aomori prefectures, 
Hirosaki was what is now Aomori Prefecture.)
	Otobe Town has districts of Sakaehama, which means ``thriving 
beach'' in Japanese, and Toyohama, which means ``rich beach'' in 
Japanese.  Those names remind us of the good old days.  After 1917 
(Taishou 6), large schools of herring disappeared from Otobe.
	[See Yoichi Town in Shiribeshi sub-prefecture and Esashi Town 
in Hiyama sub-prefecture for herring fishing.]

#4  In December 1868 (Meiji 1), during the Boshin War, the Tokugawa 
Shogunate forces advanced to the castle town of the Matsumae Domain 
(now Matsumae Town).  It was November of the lunar calendar used at the 
time.
	The Matsumae Domain's forces escaped to Tate Castle in Assabu. 
Tate Castle fell too.  They escaped to Otobe.  The lord of the Matsumae 
Domain escaped to Hirosaki (now Aomori Prefecture), and the rest of the 
Matsumae Domain's forces surrendered.  Villagers in Otobe hid Matsumae 
soldiers by dressing them in farmer's clothes.
	[See Hakodate City in Oshima sub-prefecture for the Boshin War. 
See Assabu Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for the end of the Matsumae 
Domain.]
 
#5  A bus stop ``Otobe-juuji-gai'' is located near the town hall.  The 
name ``juuji-gai'' is Japanese.  It means ``cross, road.''  The word 
``juu-ji'' means ``ten, character.''  The shape of the Kanji character 
for ten (``juu [\u5341]'' is a cross.
	The place name``Juuji-gai'' can be found also in Fukagawa, 
Hakodate, Kushiro, Okushiri, Otaru, Shikaoi, Rumoi, and Yoichi in 
Hokkaidou.
	[See Otaru City in Shiribeshi sub-prefecture for Okusawa-juuji-
gai.]
	The Kanji character ``juu'' is mysterious.  It becomes ``10,'' 
``1,'' and ``0.''  For example, ''juu'' means 10, ``juu-go'' means 15, 
and ``ni-juu'' means 20.
	* * *
	In contrast to cross road (``juu-ji-gai''), castle towns in 
Honshuu island have T-junctions (``tei-ji-ro'') and crank-shaped roads 
(``kaguino-te'').  The Kanji character ``tei [\u4E01]'' resembles the 
letter ``T'' in both shape and pronunciation.
	Those complicated roads in castle towns were constructed for 
defensive purposes.  During the period of motorization, those 
complicated roads were obstructs for automobile traffic. Today, some of 
them are used for sightseeing.
	[See Toubetsu Town in Ishikari sub-prefecture for crank-shaped 
road.]
	Motorization in Japan started after the late 1960s.  My father 
bought Nissan Cherry in the 1970s.  The novel ``The Grapes of Wrath'' 
depicts that the motorization in the USA started in the early 20th 
century.

#6  The name ``Guen-na-dai'' in Otobe Town signifies Guen-na period 
(1615-1624) in the Edo era.  A fishing ground was built in the period.  
	Hanaiso-suwa Shrine near the fishing port of Toyohama was 
built in 1617.  Fishing ports in Otobe are very old.
	The tourist site Cape Shibi-no-saki was included in Kabashira 
village.  The fishing port of Toyohama was also included in Kabashira 
village.
	Kabashira is a funny name.  It means ``mosquito pillar'' in 
Japanese.  The name comes from ``kapara-sirar'' in Ainu language.  It 
means ``flat, rock.''  (Once, I saw a large mosquito pillar in a hotel 
room in a tropical region.) 
	As for Shira-fura cliff, I guess that the name comes from 
``sirar-hu-ra'' in Ainu language, which means ``rock, raw, intestine.'' 
The eroded cliff looks like intestines of fish.
