(AV 2000-2010), PRECIPI 859 MM; COUNTRY SIGN = MAP OF ISLAND.
 
LOCATION

Okushiri [o-ku-shi-ri] [\u5965\u5C3B] is a town in Hiyama sub-
prefecture, south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').  The area is Okushiri island 
in the Sea of Japan.  Okushiri is the second largest island in 
Hokkaidou after Rishiri.
	The area of Okushiri is about the same size as Lake Saroma. 
Coastal terraces are located to the east, paddy fields to the south, 
and coastal cliffs to the west and north.  Forests cover 86 percent of 
the area.

NAME

The name ``Okushiri'' comes from ``i-kus-un-sir'' in Ainu language.  It 
means ``it, over there, exist, island.''  Or, it comes from ``i-kus-
sir'' in Ainu language.  It means ``it, over there, island.''  Both 
signified Okushiri island, which is located across the sea as seen from 
Kumaishi.

HISTORY

In the Edo era, the Matsumae Domain built Kujiri-basho (a trading 
place) in Okushiri island.  Herring fishing prospered through the Edo 
era to the Meiji period.
	In 1879 (Meiji 12), an administrative office (``kochou-
yakuba'') was built for the villages of Tsurikake [\u91E3\u61F8], 
Akaishi [\u8D64\u77F3], Yakushi [\u85AC\u5E2B], and Aonae [\u9752
\u82D7].
	In 1906 (Meiji 39), Okushiri Village (2nd-class municipality) 
was established by the merger of four villages.  In 1966 (Shouwa 41), 
Okushiri Town was established.
	[See the note of Matsumae Town for 2nd-class municipality.]

TOWN HALL, TRAFFIC

The town hall of Okushiri is located in Okushiri district to the east.  
Other built-up areas are located in Aonae district to the south and 
Kamui-waki district (now Yunohama district) to the west.
	Regarding transportation, Heart Land Ferry connects ports of 
Okushiri, Setana, and Esashi.  Okushiri Airport opened in 1974 in Aonae 
district.  Hokkaidou Air System connects Okushiri and Hakodate 
airports. 

INDUSTRY

Distinctive industries in Okushiri are fishing, food processing, and 
sightseeing.  STATISTICS OF AGRICULTURE = pasture 41 hectares in 2015, 
paddy rice 37, and orchards 31; dairy cows X (concealed) in 2015 and 
beef cattle X.  STATISTICS OF FISHERIES = squid (flying squid 417 tons 
in 2017, other squid 8), sea urchins 111, Pacific cod 69, octopus 59, 
	(continued) --> atka mackerel 58, shellfish 22 (abalone, 
Sakuragai [mactra], whelks), right-eye flounder 7, puffer fish 5, 
seaweed 5, olive flounder 4, yellowtail 1, herring - (zero), other fish 
52, and other marine animals 23.
	As for food processing, local specialties are rice wine 
(``sake'') and wine.  As for sightseeing, Nabetsuru Rock is located 
near the ferry port.  It is the icon of the island, 
	The country sign (gateway sign) of Okuhsiri is a map of the 
island.  It illustrates strange shaped rocks and Bentenguu Shrine.  
Okushiri Tsunami Museum is located in Aonae district.  #1  #2  #3

NOTE

#1  In the past, Okushiri was the island of alcohol prohibition.  
 (Alcohol prohibition is called ``kinshu'' in Japanese.)   When 
the herring catch was poor, fishermen drunk, and quarreled very much.  
So, village chief (``kochou'') banned drinking alcohol.  Prohibition 
lasted from 1885 to 1890.
	Today, rice wine (``sake'') and wine are the specialties of 
Okushiri.  There is an ``Ordinance to promote toasts with Okushiri's 
local rice wine.''  (Japanese people became more polite when they 
drink.) 
	[See Asahikawa City in Kamikawa sub-prefecture for rice wine.  
See Ikeda Town in Tokachi sub-prefecture for wine.]

#2  Okushiri island is located near the boundary between the Eurasian 
Plate and North American Plate.  In July 1993, the Okushiri Earthquake, 
happened and killed 230 people.  The magnitude was 7.8.  The disaster 
was due to tidal waves (``tsunami''), fires, and landslides.
	Being close to the epicenter, the first tidal wave arrived two 
to three minutes after the earthquake.  Tidal waves killed 198 people. 
Soon after the earthquake, television channels broadcast live footage 
from the sky.  In that night, Aonae district was burning.
	In 1998, the town declared ``completion of recovery.'' In 2001, 
Tsunami Museum opened.
	* * *
	The Sanriku Coast in the Touhoku region was hit by tidal waves. 
At an elementary school along the coast, all children could escape from 
the massve tidal waves in 2011.
	 The grandparents taught their children the phrase ``tsunami-
tendenko (tidal wave, alone).''  This means that if a large earthquake 
occurs, you must escape alone as soon as possible.

#3  These are strange shaped rocks in Okushiri island; (1) Nabe-tsuru 
Rock, which resembles a handle of iron pot, (2) Kabuto Rock (warrior's 
helmet rock), (3) Hoya Rock (sea pineapple rock), (4) Mottate Rock 
(erection rock), and (4) Muean-jima (lonely island).
	The shape of Nabe-tsuru Rock was changed by a large earthquake 
in 1993.  It was restored.  There are unique stories with the unique 
rocks.  A remote island exerts a strong fascination over some people.
