LOCATION

Setana [se-ta-na] is a town in Hiyama sub-prefecture, south Hokkaidou 
(`dou-nan'').  Setana is located in the west of the Oshima Peninsula.  
The area faces the Sea of Japan.  Cape Obana is the western tip of 
Hokkaidou island.  Ordinary tourists cannot go to the western tip, 
because it is a steep sea cliff.  #1
 	The area of Setana was newly delimited in 2005 by the merger of 
three towns; Taisei [\u5927\u6210], Kita-hiyama [\u5317\u6A9C\u5C71], 
and Setana [\u702C\u68DA] (from south to north).
	The name Taisei means ``big success'' in Japanese.  It was 
named by local residents when Kudou [\u4E45\u9060] Village and 
Kaitorima [\u8C9D\u53D6\u6F97] Villages were merged in 1955.  The name 
Kita-hiyama means ``north Hiyama (cypress mountain)'' in Japanese.
	[See Hiyama sub-prefecture for the name ``Hiyama.'']
	The name ``Setana'' comes from ``seta-rupespe-nay'' in Ainu 
language.  It means ``dog, cross, river.''  It signified a place near 
the Baba River, which flows the center of the old Setana Town.  Large 
rocks stand near the mouth of the river.
	The rocks are Sanbon-sugui-iwa (Three-ceders Rocks) and 
Rousoku-iwa (Candle Rock).  Sanbon-sugui-iwa rocks stand from the sea 
and Rousoku-iwa rock stands at the Port of Setana.  They look like 
dogs.  #2

HISTORY

In the Edo era, the Matsumae Domain established three trading places 
(``basho'') for fishing.  They were located in Kudou, Futoro, and 
Setanai (from south to north).  The places thrived from herring 
fishing.  (Futoro was located at the mouth of the Futoro River that 
flows through the former Kita-hiyama Town.)
	After the Meiji period, three counties were established in 1869 
(Meiji 2).  They were Kudou, Futoro, and Setana.  The following is the 
history of the former three towns;

OLD TAISEI TOWN; In 1872 (Meiji 5), Kudou branch of the Hokkaidou 
Development Commission was established.  In 1880 (Meiji 13), the 
administrative office (``kochou-yakuba'') of Issouma [\u4E00\u8258
\u6F97] village was established.
	The administrative office of Issouma village covered other five 
villages; Oota [\u592A\u7530], Uekotan [\u4E0A\u53E4\u4E39], Sansouma 
[\u4E09\u8258\u6F97], Hikata-tomari [\u65E5\u65B9\u6CCA], and Yunoshiri 
[\u6E6F\u5C3B].
	In the same year, the administrative office of Hiratanai 
[\u5E73\u7530\u5185] was established.  It covered other two villages; 
Kaitorima and Nagaiso [\u9577\u78EF].  In 1881 (Meiji 14), the 
administrative office of Kudou village was established by the merger of 
Issouma, Sansouma, and Hikata-tomari.
	In 1902 (Meiji 35), Kudou Village (2nd-class municipality) was 
established by the merger of Kudou, Oota, Uekotan, and Yunoshiri.  In 
1923 (Taishou 12), Kaitorima Village (2nd-class municipality) was 
established by the merger of Kaitorima, Hiratanai, and Nagaiso.
	In 1955 (Shouwa 30), Taisei Village was established by the 
merger of Kudou and Kaitorima.  In 1966 (Shouwa 41), Taisei Town was 
established.
	[See the note of Matsumae Town for 1st-class and 2nd-class 
municipalities.] 

OLD KITA-HIYAMA TOWN; In 1879 (Meiji 12), an administrative office 
(``kochou-yakuba'') was established for four villages in Futoro county; 
Futoro [\u592A\u6AD3], Gorota [\u53E4\u6AD3\u591A], Raruishi [\u826F
\u7460\u77F3], and Udomari [\u9D5C\u6CCA].
	In 1902 (Meiji 35), the administrative office of Higashi-setana 
[\u6771\u702C \u68DA] village was established.  It was separated from 
Setana village.
 	In 1906 (Meiji 39), Futoro Village (2nd-class municipality) was 
established by the merger of Futoro, Gorota, Raruishi, and Udomari.  In 
the same year, Higashi-setana Village (2nd-class municipality) was 
established.
	In 1953 (Shouwa 28), Higashi-setana Town was established.  In 
1955 (Shouwa 30), Kita-hiyama Town was established by the merger of 
Higashi-setana Town and Futoro Village.

OLD SETANA TOWN; In 1879 (Meiji 12), two administrative offices 
(``kochou-yakuba'') were established for five villages in Setana 
county; Setana, Baikatsu [\u6885\u82B1\u90FD], Nakauta [\u4E2D\u6B4C], 
Abura [\u867B\u7F85], and Shimauta [\u5CF6\u6B4C].
	In 1897 (Meiji 30), Toshibetsu village was separated from 
Setana village.  It was what is now Imakane Town, Hiyama sub-
prefecture.
	In 1902 (Meiji 35), Setana Village (2nd-class municipality) was 
established by the merger of five villages in Setana county.  Higashi-
setana village was separated from Setana Village.  (This means that an 
administrative office was built in Higashi-setana village).
	In 1919 (Taishou 8), Setana Village (1st-class municipality) 
was established.  In 1921 (Taishou 10), Setana Town was established.

TOWN HALL, TRAFFIC

The town hall of Setana is located near the mouth of the Toshibetsu 
River (Shiribeshi-toshibetsu River).  It used to be the town hall of 
Kita-hiyama Town.  National Route 229 (Hiyama-kokudou) runs along the 
Sea of Japan.  #3
	National Route 230 (Pirika-kokudou) separates from National 
Route 229 near the town hall.  National Route 230 crosses the Oshima 
Peninsula.  Formerly, the Setana Line of the Japanese National 
Railways (Kokutetsu) ran along National Route 230.  The railway 
connected Setana Station and Kun-nui Station in Oshamanbe Town.
	The Port of Setana has a ferry line to Okushiri island.  The 
windmills near the port are the first offshore windmills in the 
country.  In the built-up area of the former Setana Town, there was a 
clinic run by Guinko Oguino.  She was the first female medical doctor 
in the country.  #4

INDUSTRY

Distinctive industries in Setana are fishing, paddy rice cultivation, 
and dairy farming.  STATISTICS OF AGRICULTURE = pasture 2,046 hectares 
