	It is located at the top of a rocky mountain.  Bears live. 
Visitors are like climbers.  They will pray for a safety descent at the 
shrine.  In the past, mountaineering was a religious training.

#2  On the map published by Takeshirou Matsuura in 1859, Haha-gawa (now 
Baba River) and Setaruheshi-nai are written together (http://
koukita.github.io/touzaiezo/map/).
	Tadashi Okudaira wrote that the upper course of the Baba River 
was called the Setanai River.  The Sanbon-sugui-iwa rocks, which 
Ainu people saw as dogs (``seta''), are located at the mouth of the 
Baba River.  [By World Encyclopedia (T. Okudaira et al. 2007.)]
	I asked the town hall where the Setani River was.  They 
answered that the Setanai River would signify what is now the 
Toshibetsu River (Shiribeshi-toshibetsu River).  They showed a map of 
Setanai Basho (Setanai trading place) as evidence.  The map was drawn 
in the Ansei period (1855-1860) in the Edo era.
	Hiyama and Oshima sub-prefectures have a long history of 
Japanese settlement.  Some river names and place names were changed 
from Ainu language to Japanese.  These are examples;
	(1) The Baba River in Setana Town, whose old name may have been 
the Setanai River.  (2) The Hime River in Otobe Town, whose old name 
was the Otohe River.  (3) The Torizaki River in Mori Town, whose old 
name was the Oniushi River.
	[See Oshamanbe Town in Oshima sub-prefecture for typical river 
names in Ainu language.]
	As for the name ``Seta-nai'' (``dog, river'' in Ainu language), 
there is an Ainu legend; ``Once upon a time, large dogs came down from 
the mountains.  They were messengers of god.  They went into the sea 
and turned into rocks.''
	During a bus excursion, a student heard this topic from an 
elderly man who was walking National Route 229; ``During the Okushiri 
Earthquake, tidal waves (``tsunami'') surrounded Sanbon-sugui Rocks and 
reached this highway.  After the water subsided, sea urchins and 
flounders were left on this highway.''
	[See Okushiri Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for the Okushiri 
Earthquake.]
 
#3  National Route 229 runs along the coast.  It runs inland 
near Cape Obana.  Cape Obana is the western tip of Hokkaidou island.
It is located at the border between the former Taisei Town and the 
former Kita-hiayama Town.  
	There are strangely shaped rocks along the coast; Mother Bear 
and Cub Rock, Mammoth Rock, and Raccoon Rock.
 
#4  Guinko Oguino (1851-1913) was born in Tawarase village (now 
Kumagaya City, Saitama Prefecture).  In 1885, she passed medical 
practitioner's examination and opened a clinic for gynecology and 
obstetrics.  She became the first female medical doctor in the country. 
He clinic was located in Yushima, Tokyo.
	In 1891, her husband, Yukiyoshi Shikata, started developing 
Immanuel district.  Immanuel was located what is now Imakane Town, 
Hiyama sub-prefecture.  Immanuel was developed by Christians.  It was 
located upstream of the Shiribeshi-toshibetsu River. 
	[See Imakane Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for the name 
``Immanuel.'']
	In 1894, Guinko Oguino moved to Immanuel.  Her husband failed 
in development and became a missionary.  In 1897, she moved to Setana 
Setana and opened a clinic.  (Setana is located near the mouth of the 
Shiribeshi-toshibetsu River.)
	In 1903, she went to Sapporo.  She wanted to open a larger 
clinic in Sapporo, however, she was told that her medical technique was 
20 years' behind.  She returned to Setana.  In 1905, her husband died. 
In 1908, she returned to Tokyo.
	* * *
	As for a medical doctor, I lived in a teachers' apartment in 
Sapporo City.  Next to the apartment was a clinic for internal medicine 
and pediatrics.  The elderly doctor said; ``I was originally internist. 
When I added pediatrics in this clinic, my friends scorned me.  But I 
had to raise my children.''
	He was proud that his three sons became medical doctors.  When 
I went to the clinic with the influenza, he said; ``The latest machine 
to test the influenza is expensive.  The debt remains with my son, 
ha, ha, ha (laugh).''
	After his sudden death, one of his sons came from a hospital 
and succeeded the clinic for about a year.  Then, the clinic was 
demolished and an apartment was built.

#5  A graduation thesis submitted to Faculty of Letters, Hokkaidou 
University, was on the theme of rice wine production in Setana Town. 
The following is an excerpt from it. 
	``The producers of the rice wine are farmers.  They cultivate 
paddy rice and brew rice wine.  They sell two trade names of sake. 
One is Guinko-monogatari (Guinko's story) and the other is Yoshiko.
	Guinko-monogatari is made from the brewery rice variety 
``Guinpuu.''  It is cultivated by rice-duck farming.  (Rice-duck 
farming is a kind of organic agriculture.)  Yoshiko is made from 
the ordinal rice variety ``Kirara 397.''
	The producers of the rice wine wanted to use the names Kita-
hiyama and Suisen.  The name ``Kita-hiyama'' is the former town's 
name.  The word ``suisen'' means daffodil in Japanese.  It is the 
town's flower.  Those names had been already trademarked.
	 For the rocal rice wine, the name ``Guinko'' was selected 
because she was a famous female doctor in Setana.  The name ``Yoshiko''
was selected because it is a common name in the town, such as the wife 
and mother of the rice wine producers.
	The cultivation of brewery rice is difficult in Hokkaidou.  The 
grain of brewery rice is larger than that of ordinary rice.  (The rice 
wine category `guinjou'' is made using the core of brewery rice.)  The 
rice wine producers in Setana also use the ordinary rice variety 
(Kirara 397). 
	[See Uryuu Town in Sorachi sub-prefecture and Pippu Town in 
Kamikawa sub-prefecture for Kirara 397.]
	* * *
	Hokkaidou's wine is also made from ordinary grapes, such 
as Naiagara.  (``Ordinary grapes'' means table grapes in Japan.)  Also, 
locally grown mountain grapes (Yama-budou) are used.
	As for the brewery rice variety, Yamada-nishiki is the most 
famous.  It has been used for the rice wine made in the Nada region 
(now Hyougo Prefecture, in the central part of Honshuu island).  Nada 
is famous for rice wine production.
	The Nada's rice wine was shipped to Ezo (now Hokkaidou) by 
North-bound ships.  It is said that the rice wine transported by ship 
tastes better.
	[See Asahikawa City in Kamikawa sub-prefecture, Mashike Town in 
Rumoi sub-prefecture, and Kuriyama Town in Sorachi sub-prefecture for 
rice wine.  See Ikeda Town in Tokachi sub-prefecture for wine.]
