|     IMAKANE      |
|                  |
|  MAP 2 - NO. 18  |
 ------------------
DATA

AREA 568 KM2 (2010), FOREST 455, CULTIVATED 53; COUNTY = SETANA [\u702C
\u68DA]; POP 6,186 (2010), 7,710 (1990); MEAN ANNUAL TEMP 7.9 C (AV 
1981-2010), PRECIPI 1,327 MM, SNOW 657 CM; COUNTRY SIGN = SEA COWS.
  
LOCATION

Imakane [i-ma-ka-ne] [\u4ECA\u91D1] is a town in Hiyama sub-prefecture, 
south Hokkaidou (``dou-nan'').  Imakane is located inland in the Oshima 
Peninsula.  The area corresponds to the midstream and upstream of the 
Shiribeshi-toshibetsu River, which flows to the Sea of Japan.  Local 
residents call it Toshibetsu River.  Its downstream is Setana Town.

NAME

The name ``Imakane'' is Japanese.  It is derived from two pioneers, 
Toujirou Imamura and Ishirou Kanamori (Ima- and Kane-).  Both pioneers 
were graduates of Tokyo Professional School (now Waseda University).  
#1

HISTORY

In the Edo era, the Matsumae Domain gathered gold dust in the upstream 
of the Shiribetsu-toshibetsu River.  In the Meiji period, there were 
agate and manganese mines.
	In 1893 (Meiji 26), the two pioneers settled in what is now 
Imakane district. In the same year, a group of Christians (Kirisuto-
kyou-dantai) settled in Immanuel district.  #2
	In 1897 (Meiji 30), the administrative office (``kochou-
yakuba'') of Toshibetsu [\u5229\u5225] village was established.  The 
village was separated from Setana village.
	In 1906 (Meiji 39), Toshibetsu Village (2nd-class municipality) 
was established.  In 1929 (Shouwa 4), Toshibetsu Village (1st-class 
municipality) was established.  In 1947 (Shouwa 22), Imakane Town was 
established.  At the time, Toshibetsu was renamed to Imakane.
	[See the note of Matsumae Town for 1st-class and 2nd-class 
municipalities.] 

TOWN HALL, TRAFFIC

The town hall of Imakane is located along the middle reaches of the 
Shiribeshi-toshibetsu River.  National Route 230 (Pirika-kokudou or 
Hanaishi-douro) runs.  #3  #4
	In the past, the Setana Line ran along the Shiribeshi-
toshibetsu River.  The railway crossed the Oshima peninsula.  It 
connected Setana Station on the Sea of Japan side and Kun-nui Station 
along Uchiura Bay on the Pacific Ocean side.
	(Setana Station was located in the former Setana Town.  Kun-nui 
Station on the Hakodate Main Line is located in Oshamanbe Town).

INDUSTRY

Distinctive industries in Imakane are agriculture, animal husbandry, 
and forestry. STATISTICS OF AGRICULTURE = pasture 1,446 hectares in 
2015, paddy rice 1,414, beans (soybeans 376, adzuki beans 208), 
potatoes 396, wheat 273, fodder 229, sugar beets 117, buckwheat 69,
	(continued) --> carrots 32, broccoli 24, barley 19, tomatoes 
13, onions 5, and other grains 24; dairy cows 2,021 head in 2015 and 
hogs and pigs X (concealed).
 	Potatoes are sold with the trade-name ``Imakane-danshaku.''  As 
for animal husbandry, swine farms of Nippon Ham Group are distributed 
in the mountains.  #5
	As for sightseeing, Pirika Dam is located near Pirika Pass. 
The dam has a long concrete dyke.  It stands out along National Route 
230.  The country sign (gateway sign) of the town is Piiri and Piika, 
which are nicknames for sea cow fossils excavated from the dam 
construction site.  #6

NOTE
 
#1  As for the name ``Imakane,'' the name of the post office is Imagane 
(not Imakane).  The name of the former railroad station was Imagane. 
The name on the topographical map by Geographical Survey Institute is 
Imakane.
	Imakane Town's former name was Toshibetsu.  It comes from 
``tus-pet'' in Ainu language.  It means ``snake (or rope), river.''  
Or, it comes from ``to-us-pet'' in Ainu language.  It means ``pond, 
many, river.''  Both signified the Shiribeshi-toshibetsu River. 
	The Shiribeshi-toshibetsu River was ranked as the cleanest 
river of the country.  The clean river ranking is listed in Current 
Water Quality of Class-A Rivers in the Country (Zenkoku-ikkyuu-kasen-
no-suishitsu-genkyou), which is published by the Ministry of Land, 
Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism.
	[See Rankoshi Town in Shiribeshi sub-prefecture for the 
cleanest rivers.] 

#2  The Christian group settled in Immanuel tried to make their utopia. 
The name ``Immanuel'' means ``God with us'' in Hebrew.  It was located 
in what is now Kamioka district.  The name ``Kamioka'' means ``god 
hill'' in Japanese.
	The first female doctor in the country, Guinko Oguino, came to 
Immanuel.  Her husband was a member of the Christian group.
	[See Setana Town in Hiyama sub-prefecture for her clinic.]
	On the map published by Takeshiro Matsuura in 1859 (http://
koukita.github.io/touzaiezo/map/), there is a place name written as 
Imanpetsu.  It may come from ``i-ma-un-pet'' in Ainu language, which 
means ``it, burn (skewers for grilled fish), exist, river.''  Maybe, 
the Christian group imagined Immanuel from the pronunciation.
	(Updated in 2024; The place name on the map may be Imashipetsu. 
It may come from ``i-ma-si-pet'' in Ainu language, which means ``it, 
burn, large, river.''  Some Katakana characters are difficult to 
distinguish such as ``n'' and ''shi,'' and ``shi'' and ``tsu.'')

#3  Hanaishi district is located near Pirika Dam.  The word 
``hanaishi'' is Japanese.  It means ``menou'' in Japanese and 
``agate [a'get]'' in English.  Hanaishi was the largest agate mine in 
the country in the Meiji period.  The agate was shipped to Fukui 
Prefecture and carved into ornaments (Wakasa-menou-zaiku). 
	* * *
	Nowadays, agate is mainly imported from Brazil.  When I visited 
Sao Paulo, I entered a souvenir shop.  A Japanese man who also was 
looking souvenirs recommended me to buy agate chopstick rests.
	While pointing to various colored chopstick rests, he said, 
``Agate is artificially colored, but this is natural.''  It was brown. 
He was the president of a construction company and knew many things 
including good restaurants in Sao Paulo.

#4  Near the center of Imakane Town, a large loop bridge stands out. 
It continues up to Hikaridai district, which is an agricultural area 
on a hill.  The loop bridge looks like an expressway, but it is the 
agricultural road called ``Nou-men-douro.''
	The agricultural road (Nou-men-douro) is constructed using 
gasoline tax.  It is considered as a deduction of the gasoline tax that 
was used for agricultural machinery. 
	Other loop bridges in Hokkaidou can be seen in Sunagawa (Sorach 
sub-prefecture), Toyoura (Iburi sub-prefecture), and Asari district in 
Otaru (Shiribeshi sub-prefecture).

#5  ``Danshaku'' is a potato cultivar for eat.  The word ``danshaku''
means ``baron'' in Japanese.  Danshaku potatoes are as pouplar as May-
queen potatoes.  (The major potato cultivar for processing is Kona-
fubuki.)
	Imakane potatoes have a reputation for quality.  The potato 
cultivated area in Imakane is smaller than that of municipalities in 
Tokachi sub-prefecture.  The land per farm in Imakane is also smaller 
than that of municipalities in Tokachi sub-prefecture.  (Tokachi is 
famous for potato production.)
	Farmers in Imakane take time on their smaller land.  In the 
case of potato cultivation, they remove ``nora-imo (stray potatoes),'' 
which are the rest of the former harvest.  The so-called stray potatoes 
give a bad impact on the next cultivation.
	A former high school teacher said; ``Potatoes are cultivated 
after potatoes in south Hokkaidou (`dou-nan,' including Imakane Town). 
Potatoes are cultivated in crop rotation in east Hokkaidou (`dou-tou,' 
including Tokachi sub-prefecture).''
	In Tokachi, potatoes are cultivated after sugar beets.  Then, 
beans or wheat are cultivated after potatoes.  The so-called stray 
potatoes are killed by the cold temperature.  However, recently, not 
all stray potatoes are killed because of climate change.
	[See Shihoro Town in Tokachi sub-prefecture for potatoes.  See 
Kucchan Town in Shiribeshi sub-prefecture for Danshaku potatoes.  See 
Assabu Town for May-queen potatoes.]
 
#6  The width of Pirika Dam is 1,480 meters.  It is the longest 
concrete dam in the country.
	The dam was constructed between 1975 and 1991 at the confluence 
of the three rivers; the Shiribeshi-toshibetsu River, the Pirikabetsu
River, and the Chuushibetsu River.
	Pirika Dam is used for power generation, irrigation, and flood 
control.  The driftwood collected from the dam lake is distributed free 
of charge for personal use, such as for wood-burning stoves and 
gardening.
	Kur [ku-a] Plaza Pirika is located in front of the dam.  It 
includes a hot spring, a ski resort, and a restaurant.  The specialty 
of the restaurant is dam curry.  Rice is blocking the curry like a dam.
	[See Hakodate City in Oshima sub-prefecture for curry and 
rice.]
	In the upstream of the Pirikabetsu River, there is Okupirika 
hot spring.  It is located along Prefectural Route 999.  The name 
``Pirika-betsu'' means ``beautiful river'' in Ainu language.  The Kanji 
characters for Pirika [\u7F8E\u5229\u6CB3] also means ``beautiful, 
gain, river.''
